commit_message:
Small refactoring for Sahara platform test

* Method "_test_image" was renamed into "check_image"
  because we check image but not test

* Steps to list node group templates and cluster templates were removed
  because sanity tests have these checks

* Some messages were corrected

* Sahara platform test was renamed

Change-Id: I5ca9c25ed2e04eca09c8632a6e2757706990b2f9

commit_message:
Change test function from snapshot to backup

According to test function name 'test_backup_invalid_state',
the usage of functions should be backup instead of snapshot.

commit_message:
Compute: use an instance object in terminate_instance

The instance in terminate_instance is an object. Use the object format
when locking the instance.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I7b40f0dcdbe1866443388a83957c4ebafadd978e

commit_message:
Introduce directories as possible arguements

With this patch it's possible to scan specific files for issues or
to scan testable files in specific directories for issues.

Change-Id: I5a2027adb380fb4c976a2f412cccf8ece197ae97

commit_message:
Fix disk_allocation_ratio on filter_scheduler.rst

There is an option "disk_allocation_ratio" in DiskFilter instead of
a typo "disk_allocation_ration".
This patch fixes the typo on filter_scheduler.rst.

Change-Id: Iad4951fbdca97eccb956c42270bfc170fc7c7dac

[{'created': '2014-09-29 08:54:03.000000000', 'message': 'Extend XML unicode test coverage

Extends the coverage of the servers XML serialization test to
cover unicode values. Fixes common function to be handle fields
being unicode. No actual bug fix, but this is test coverage which
we always should have, and an investigation into another unicode
bug revealed the missing coverage and problem with the tests
not handline unicode values.

commit_message:
Extend XML unicode test coverage

Extends the coverage of the servers XML serialization test to
cover unicode values. Fixes common function to be handle fields
being unicode. No actual bug fix, but this is test coverage which
we always should have had, and an investigation into another unicode
bug revealed the missing coverage and problem with the tests
not handling unicode values.

Change-Id: I6255ad1cf9a3429c0d87cb6709c11c1b65df9ba5
Related-Bug: 1279172

commit_message:
Remove init for object list in api layer

There is a list initialization in api layer server code,
because objectListBase already handles that init process,
so remove it from api layer.

Change-Id: I84b0641ec2088d2920d3757ac1a99c301fc0bcb0

commit_message:
Add vlan_ids parameter

  'vlan_ids' parameter was added to l23network puppet module. Added
  this parameter in nailgun accordingly.
  Created NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer60 for adding 'vlans_id'
  to the network scheme attributes.

Change-Id: I5e41abf9ccf490e6c67d04ca324f90df0c6ca87c
Related-Bug: 1305600

starts.

commit_message:
VMware: add support for default pbm policy

This is part of the blueprint vmware-spbm-support.
If there is no defined storage policy in the flavor then the default
storage policy will be used. This patch set adds in the definition of
the default storage policy and validates it existence when the service
starts.

DocImpact
    - pbm_enabled - enables storage policy based placement
    - pbm_default_policy - the default policy that will be used if there
      is none in the flavor
    - pbm_wsdl_location (optional) - PBM service WSDL file location URL.
      e.g. file:///opt/SDK/spbm/wsdl/pbmService.wsdl.

Co-authored-by: Radoslav Gerganov <rgerganov@vmware.com>

Change-Id: I1fc5a99c153d815ea735dccda9d2958dba52ec49

commit_message:
Fix os-svc-install

The 'a' option was missing from the getops set of available options
in os-svc-restart.  This is causing CI failures in patces with an
"illegal operation -- a" error.[1]  This patch adds the 'a' option
to os-svc-restart.

[1] Ib3bc5c47de1b8bb6006530d56e9d47c3763af7b5

Change-Id: I527c5b0cda0cda7877d23422702517760c1bf340

commit_message:
Add ability to enable debug logging on seed

Because our seed uses a static config json we require special logic to
enable debug logging on it.

Change-Id: If38d9947e6e70ce537219caf1e2835285351d960

(1 comment)

I think that the 2 IFs to guard iptables-save/restore are unnecessary and we should keep the block of code mutually exclusive to the specific Distro.

This keeps the future changes here safe too when we support more distros. [I think] It will be unnecessarily harder for the future implementation to test all distros for such a trivial change for iptables.

How do we resolve this?'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-08-13 09:01:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-2

What is our reason to extend the usage of add-rule when the direction is to use os-iptables-stateful and os-iptables-stateless, as per https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/os-iptables-scripts?'}, {'account_id': 6969, 'date': '2014-08-13 17:14:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

JP the main reason is that add-rule is used in 33 different places and os-iptables-stateful is used in 0 places.

While there are advantages to os-iptables-tables until an effort is put in to actually use it we should go with this.

Getting consistent iptables rules is more important.'}, {'account_id': 10007, 'date': '2014-08-13 17:18:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

My understanding is that we've only ever supported distros that have a deny-all rule by default - and only because we had to in order to get things to work at all.

I initially didn't like this change as I thought it was quite a departure from what we currently do; but from reading the comments I get the sense that this change is intended to let people using Debian distros, who apply a deny-all rule, to leverage the work we've already done rather than having to create their own ruleset.

I'm quite in favour of this, but I'd like to see it explicitly mentioned in the commit message. Currently, the commit message explains what is being done, but not why.

(As a further guide - the first point in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Information_in_commit_messages suggests not assuming that the reviewer understands what problem you're trying to solve)"}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-09-10 23:00:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

I'd suggest the body of the commit message be something along the lines of:

We currently use the add-rule script to create iptables rules that allow the cloud we deployed to function.

These rules are required on RedHat based distros that have a default deny-all policy; but they're also useful on Debian distros, where many operators turn on a deny-all policy as part of locking down their environment. It would be useful if these operators could leverage the work we've already done to get their environments working.

This change adds a check for Debian and allows the add-rule script to run, as a first step towards full support for Debian-based distros.

Also, install.d installs iptables and there
is a Debian specific change.

Change-Id: Iea773d37b18c15a417896e93e29bcdc1e20096ac
Closes-Bug: #1351412"}, {'account_id': 10007, 'date': '2014-09-11 20:51:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 20:51:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Verified+1

commit_message:
Support Debian distro for iptables

We currently use the add-rule script to create iptables rules that allow
the cloud we deployed to function.

These iptable rules are required on RedHat based distros that have a
default deny-all policy; but they're also useful on Debian distros if
the operators turn on a deny-all policy as part of locking down their
environment. It would be useful if these operators could leverage the
work RedHat has done to get the Debian distro working.

This change adds a check for Debian and allows the add-rule script to
run, as a first step towards full support for Debian-based distros.

Also, install.d installs iptables and there is a Debian specific change.

Change-Id: Iea773d37b18c15a417896e93e29bcdc1e20096ac
Closes-Bug: #1351412

commit_message:
Remove unused openstack.common.importutils

When the code in openstack.common.log was updated, it is now consuming the
importutils from oslo.utils. There are no longer local references to this
code.

Change-Id: I09ff72e307c1d5ee58388184a97a36ae183d7b0e
Partially-Implements: blueprint improve-oslo-usage

commit_message:
Add exceptions.BadRequest to the test case of reserve_fixed_ip

we change the exception of reserve_fixed_ip in fixed_ip api to
HTTPBadRequest, add this exception to tempest, and also we need
to accept HTTPNotFound exception to support juno test cases.

Change-Id: Iafd2fb82ad5d50c2f4b3f0819ac7a6f8aa901264

Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-09-29 05:50:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 (2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-09-29 08:42:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 (4 comments) Hi Aaron You did a great job here, just a few things to change: We should use bloctrans where a variable comes in after the translatable string, this in order to avoid string concatenation: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/I18n/TranslatableStrings#Use_string_formating_variables.2C_never_perform_string_concatenation Concerning &npsp; all special characters ( http://en.kioskea.net/contents/241-special-characters ) should also be in the translatable string. Indeed, a special character is a character which can differ in another language. However, translators might not be aware of html character codes... so I wonder why we use html char codes? If horizon is properly configured in UTF-8, using the utf-8 character would be far more friendly for the translator.   is an unbreakable space, so this character is a bit special. An » needs to be in translatable strings for sure, but I don't know if an unbreakable space is good in all languages. in doubt, I prefer giving the translator extra degrees of liberty by adding it in the translatable string. Akihiro, Thai and Doug, what are you opinions on   and special characters? : http://en.kioskea.net/contents/241-special-characters Thanks Aaron for the patch-set."}, {'account_id': 11881, 'date': '2014-09-29 21:06:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (7 comments) I believe I addressed using blocktrans when variables appear after a translatable string (I found several more that weren't flagged in review). I intentionally left ones where there were embedded html for example as I wasn't sure how those were handled inside of blocktrans. As for the  , I left those as were coded prior to this fix for bringing ':' inside translation blocks."}, {'account_id': 11881, 'date': '2014-09-29 21:07:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-29 21:08:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1 Merge Failed. I think we should remove it from our HTML, and instead use css for padding. Not sure if we need another patch for it, or if Aaron wants to include it in this patch. Your call Aaron =)'}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-09-30 10:11:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 (7 comments) Just a few notes (see inline comments). Concerning the html tags you mention, you can put html tags in the translatable strings but the translator will see the tags in his string. In some cases in can be useful, because in some languages you need to swap places of elements, if we have separate strings just because a part is put in strong characters, the concatenation might not render a proper translation. I don't know what would be the best here, because translators are not necessarily familiar with html tags. I leave it to your appreciation."}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2014-09-30 12:03:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 (6 comments) Aaron, I appreciate your hard work on this! commit_message:
Add ':' inside translatable (Part 1 of 2)

Punctuation needs to be included in translation since punctuation differs
depending on the language.  Along with moving ':' also replaced   with
blank space insde trans tag.    The initial review grew too large, so this
patch has been broken into 2 reviews.  Part 2 will cover the files in
openstack_dashboard/dashboard/project while Part 1 will cover the rest.

Change-Id: Ie7c2f7f66f065e0408e20d2f7351a5190fa208d7
Partially-Closes-Bug: #1369445

[{'created': '2014-10-14 00:36:02.000000000', 'message': "Fix to get exception detail with vCenter 5.1

The current child path used '/detail' is not compatible with
vCenter 5.1.

This patch adds a lookup to '/Envelope/Body/Fault/detail' to make
sure we get the detail of the exception.

Change-Id: Id5ca2d87a7cba8b531a4c54111505e72c70df021
"}]
commit_message:
Fix to get exception detail with vCenter 5.1

The current child path used '/detail' is not compatible with
vCenter 5.1.

This patch adds a lookup to '/Envelope/Body/Fault/detail' to make
sure we get the detail of the exception.

Change-Id: Id5ca2d87a7cba8b531a4c54111505e72c70df021

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Check subnet's DHCP before hosting networks

Networks which do not have any DHCP enabled subnets should not be
hosted on any of the DHCP agents

But if a subnet is updated to DHCP OFF, and if there are
no other DHCP enabled subnets for that network, we may un-host the
network, but rolled back those code changes considering the case
of overiding manual network <--> dhcpagent binding.

Change-Id: I498d588c74e53b95413e33a6afb41cbbbc319448
Closes-Bug: #1213394

commit_message:
restart_required cfg-param is bool and not string

There was a break to the previous version of the configuration
paramenters API when the configurations parameters were moved to
the database. The actual type of the restart_required parameter
should be a JSON boolean value, and not a string to be compatible
with the previous configuration parameters API.

Change-Id: If45944e25a55813ddf8f80010811da04d667ca19
Closes-Bug: #1379665

Cinder SQL scripts assume too much about the environment and the way in
which they are executed by sqlalchemy-migrate. Particularly, they manage
transactions on their own even though sqlalchemy-migrate do it itself,
plus it assumes that scripts are executed in one go (even though
standard Python DB-API 2.0 does not mention multi-statement SQL commands
to be executed on DB cursors.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Change-Id: I10c58b3af75d3ab9153a8bbd2a539bf1577de328
Closes-Bug: 1368391
'}]
commit_message:
SQL scripts should not manage transactions

Cinder SQL scripts assume too much about the environment and the way in
which they are executed by sqlalchemy-migrate. Particularly, they manage
transactions on their own even though sqlalchemy-migrate do it itself,
plus it assumes that scripts are executed in one go (even though
standard Python DB-API 2.0 does not mention multi-statement SQL commands
to be executed on DB cursors.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Change-Id: I10c58b3af75d3ab9153a8bbd2a539bf1577de328
Closes-Bug: 1368391

commit_message:
Add python-jobs to heat-templates

pep8, python26 and python27 are initially non-voting.

heat-templates has agent scripts written in python which now have
unit tests that require check jobs.

These scripts are in diskimage-builder elements, and the python
is not packaged or published.

The jobs will be made voting when they prove to be reliable.

Change-Id: If7ffa7d9b2eb2937b8dcdd73cad8adcdb3387505

commit_message:
Leverage neutronclient.openstack.common.importutils import_class

This patch allows us to drop our version of import_class in favor
of openstack.common.importutils version's.

Change-Id: Ia96f06e2dc7dfb9824377e3a7381da2732dd2c15
Closes-bug: 1365273

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Fix bad header bug in glance-replicator

When trying to use "glance-replicator livecopy" to replicate the
images from one OpenStack glance to another, it encounters "Bad
header" error for "x-image-meta-virtual-size" header. This is
because this header is not in the whitelist of v1 API headers of
form "x-image-meta-xxx".

Another problem after adding this "x-image-meta-virtual-size" to
header whitelist is that the sqlalchemy fail due to virual_size is
"None", which cannot be converted to int. To fix this problem, we
should avoid converting the None value attribute in GET
/v1/images/detail response to the header of POST /v1/images. I
added the None value check, following what the way in
glance/common/utils.py image_meta_to_http_headers() method.

Closes-Bug: #1373333

Change-Id: I13182c4e3212024a9d5663cefd2951c576961f4f

commit_message:
DB Lockwait Timeout on router-interface-delete

This patch addresses the DB Lockwait timeout
caused by two REST calls attempting to delete the
csnat_router_interface ports.

By introducing a lock the Lockwait timeout issue
is resolved.

Change-Id: I5cdb6b5eef4792aca09f45724c9c97a5e9d99ace
Closes-Bug: #1377241

Put pbr and six first in requirements list

Each of them have scenarios where it's important that they install
first.

commit_message:
Port disk_config extension for V2.1

This patch ports v2 disk_config extension to v2.1.

Unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1.
API sample file and their tests have been added.

Also added extension point of server resize V3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

commit_message:
Cleanup tenant networks plugin config creation

Cleans up the os-tenant-networks plugin config creation.
Although written in a way that the config options could be
declared in multiple places in Nova this is no longer the case
and its not something we should do anyway.

This is some prep work before porting the plugin to the
v2.1 API

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I3b8b26035654f2482b3ba9561c404b6a437ec8a2

commit_message:
Echo that qemu-img convert is running

qemu-img convert can take a few minutes to complete, or far longer
on heavily loaded systems. Notify the user that the image is
undergoing conversion to save them just seeing END PROFILING.

Change-Id: I1ad61ce5ed011b721d48e2d12fb42ef4aa5cd1f6

subject: Add query property to threshold alarms.

[{'created': '2014-10-12 03:25:20.000000000', 'message': 'Add query property to threshold alarms.

Heat had fallen behind the evolution of the Ceilometer API.
The full generality of the Ceilometer API for creating alarms was not available
through Heat templates.  In particular, the template author could stipulate
only matching metadata in the query for Samples; other very interesting
attributes, such as resource_id, could not be referenced in alarm
properties.

This change introduces a new property for OS::Ceilometer::Alarm,
namely "query".  The template can now specify a query property
instead of a matching_metadata property, and can thus reference
anything that can be referenced in a Ceilometer query.

The old matching_metadata property remains, but is now deprecated.

This change does not attempt to allow a user to give both a query
property and a matching_metadata property.  There is no need for
such, as the query parameter is strictly more expressive than
the matching_metadata property.  Note also that the python-ceilometerclient
has a lot of backward compatibility logic --- including accepting
matching_metadata --- and it attempts no merging of query and
matching_metadata.

Closes-Bug: #1326721
Change-Id: I0667db868c6f827867a5a20e4a3fa22fcad1a6a1

commit_message:
Add query property to threshold alarms.

Heat had fallen behind the evolution of the Ceilometer API.  The full
generality of the Ceilometer API for creating alarms was not available
through Heat templates.  In particular, the template author could
stipulate only matching metadata in the query for Samples; other very
interesting attributes, such as resource_id, could not be referenced
in alarm properties.

This change introduces a new property for OS::Ceilometer::Alarm,
namely "query".  The template can now specify a query property instead
of a matching_metadata property, and can thus reference anything that
can be referenced in a Ceilometer query.

The old matching_metadata property remains, and its constraints on
which samples to accept are combined with those from the query (if
any).

Note also that the python-ceilometerclient has a lot of backward
compatibility logic --- including accepting matching_metadata.  This
change adds all that logic into OS::Ceilometer::Alarm, so that it
becomes a proper client of the current Ceilometer API.

Closes-Bug: #1326721
Change-Id: I0667db868c6f827867a5a20e4a3fa22fcad1a6a1

commit_message:
Fix operation on clouds with availability-zones

In a cloud with AZs, you can get multiple entries back from the service
catalog - one for each AZ and then one that is AZ agnostic that's tied
to the region. If the region_name is plumbed all the way through, this
works as intended.

Change-Id: I3b365ea306e8111fc80830672ae8080a5d1dc8e0

commit_message:
Use timeutils from oslo.utils

Rather than sync'ing with oslo-incubator, let's use the library
oslo.utils instead. Removing the local copy of timeutils.

Change-Id: I4fbc7e7637577fcad8281897f4286690b1bbd14d
Partially-Implements: blueprint improve-oslo-usage

commit_message:
Allow multi-line config items in meta-section of local.conf

It would behave such as the contents from each meta-section in
local.conf is copied to the destination files. One exception is the multiline
options not grouped together. In that case, the contents will be grouped
together in its destination config file.

Check tests/test_config.sh for examples.

Change-Id: I8c046b558eeb98ed221f6f1a59182d4179956ced
Partial-Bug: #1374118

commit_message:
Do not assume order of lvm.tun_ofports set elements

This fixes the test_fdb_add_flows unit test that breaks with a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED
(see the bug report).

The test assumed that the lvm.tun_ofports set had
elements in a particular order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=2455351445 and
1595538922.

The fix sorts the actions output string so that it is always sorted when the
outputs are compared.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will be
addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I86b453a93f3ba09212709caf462cf3bfc5b21ee9

commit_message:
Update cinder content for Juno

I updated the cinder content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Add the python-oslo-db package because the openstack-cinder
   package depends on it, but does not install it.
2) Install the lvm2 package to remove assumption that
   distributions install it by default.
3) Enable and start LVM metadata service prior to volume
   creation.
4) Rename openstack-cinder-volume package to openstack-cinder.

This patch originates from testing on Fedora and applies to
installations on RHEL/CentOS/Fedora.

Change-Id: Idc2dbf8e60b9e79f36c3e1882fc98b61e5fddb53

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary debug/info logs of normal API ops

There are some debug/info log messages about normal API operations
in each API method, but Nova WSGI framework has already output the
similar messages. So these messages are meaningless, and this patch
removes them.

Change-Id: Ifea3edd912ec80eed2869c3f97345d403ea96c89

commit_message:
Nova-controller config setup

Configurations will exist in nova.conf. They will be read in and
set by the start script.  The mysql configuration will be
made by nova-conductor.

Change-Id: I1709ff6620b19ef5dbcf5efe8b72c329acf96123

commit_message:
Port os-networks plugin to v2.1(v3) infrastructure

Ports os-networks extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical.

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I94b7b476cbb02725a396725a379417b64afd58a7

commit_message:
sqlalchemy migration not to import model

sqlalchemy migration scripts should depend on
reflections rather than import model.py
Model denotes the latest state and will fail
if used in migration scripts

Change-Id: I4fcc3d06b96fab07ed47d5cc1fc4040395a60be8
Closes-Bug: #1380479

commit_message:
Only delete stack user project from correct domain

Check the domain ID for the project matches the configured domain from
heat.conf, so we avoid the bad outcome of deleting the user's project
when heat has been configured for stack domain users after creating
some stacks.

Conflicts:
	heat/common/heat_keystoneclient.py
	heat/tests/test_heatclient.py

Change-Id: I247e732033f44daf0de5b0efeff6c263814d13ab
Closes-Bug: #1365332

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-13 23:54:58.000000000', 'message': "Fixes Hyper-V COM initializazion race condition

The Neutron Hyper-V agent fails occasionally with a x_wmi_uninitialised_thread
exception due to lack of initialization of the COM library.

Since it's not possible to know in advance which thread is assigned to the functions
performing COM calls, this patch adds a decorator to each relevant public method
in any Hyper-V *utils module, wrapping calls in CoInitializeEx / ConUninitialize pairs.

For details:
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms695279(v=vs.85).aspx

Change-Id: Ied08ceced643093d6f56e546b600400647cbb587
Closes-Bug: #1298034
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V COM initializazion race condition

The Neutron Hyper-V agent fails occasionally with a x_wmi_uninitialised_thread
exception due to lack of initialization of the COM library.

Since it's not possible to know in advance which thread is assigned to the functions
performing COM calls, this patch adds a decorator to each relevant public method
in any Hyper-V *utils module, wrapping calls in CoInitializeEx / ConUninitialize pairs.

For details:
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms695279(v=vs.85).aspx

Change-Id: Ied08ceced643093d6f56e546b600400647cbb587
Closes-Bug: #1298034

commit_message:
Prevent excessive validation for maxPersonality limit

We have PERSONALITY property on OS::Nova::Server that defaults to {},
but code that triggers check for limits compares value of property
to None -> this property always get validated for limits (if limit is
set).

Change-Id: I552a03cd9f4ab570aa059349ab361bb50c9c0d1e
Closes-bug: #1333283
(cherry picked from commit 78b68ba0da5d6ad71397538e484fb7565333129b)

Add rally-self job

This job run task with various "dummy" scenarios to test only rally
internals. This job does not require cloud.

commit_message:
Run sideways ironic greande only on juno branches

This ironic grenade job is meant to test sideways migration within
the Juno release.  The nova code required has been dropped from
master and it will now only run against Juno.  Limit it to run only
against (proposed/stable)/juno.

Change-Id: Ibbdb547269e7bda78e2514dc8957a0cd9b1c7dae

Sean, we want to use this in openstack-manuals. I am not sure if this is a integrated project. But I think so.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-13 17:24:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Now that we have a full pypi mirror available to the CI systems, I think we're trying to switch to only managing dependencies for packages for software products. I'm not certain that the docs need to have their dependencies listed here any more, since the build jobs can install whatever they want and I believe (though am not certain) that the manuals aren't built by the distros. If that assumption is wrong, we should add this, but otherwise I think it's safe for you to just use it without listing it here."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-10-13 17:30:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Doug, requirements has one nice thing: Keeping versions in sync. And that's the benefit of having this in.

We need this change in openstack-manuals - and since we have openstack-manuals in requirements/projects.txt, we should not add anything new to openstack-manuals/test-requirements.txt AFAIU.

So, what would be the best way of handling this?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-13 17:54:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

After discussing with AJaeger in IRC and discovering that we do have distros building our manuals from source, I'm changing my mind on this. commit_message:
Add new requirement beautifulsoup4

To automatically prettify HTML files generated out of Jinja2
templates (I2f0c61006ef8885e157eb2b800080407f2bae393) in the
openstack-manuals repository when running the publishdocs job
we need to add the requirement beautifulsoup4.

Change-Id: Id1c15ea7ab5ef3295e0c14ef2b12ad96ef4acacc

commit_message:
Unit test of script hook

This test asserts the following when the script hook is invoked
with test data:
- Expected env variables are set
- Script contents matches the fake config tool contents
- Script is invoked with no arguments
- Written output files result in output values being set
- Script responding with a failure returncode propagates to the
  response

Change-Id: I1c32ec89b1ce16c25e3a29ab36e016cca5ff7835

commit_message:
Trigger cfn-init via script rather than lib

The current cfn-init software-config hook doesn't work at all
since cfn_helper is installed in a venv, not in site-packages.

This change switches to writing out metadata to
/var/cache/heat-cfntools/last_metadata and invoking cfn-init.

/var/lib/heat-cfntools/cfn-init-data cannot be used since that is
already populated with all boot metadata, which may still be used
by os-collect-config bootstrapping.

Change-Id: I7252a6f12223613b55b4b6417383673faa0d52b3
Closes-Bug: #1321513

commit_message:
Add share server id field in shares detail info

Each share in manila keeps information about share
server where this share is situated. For now shares
can be filtered using this id only by admin. But share
server id is not shown in response even to admins.

Change-Id: Iea87805b999681f41b091dc114d52244480bb488
Closes-Bug: #1379378

commit_message:
Add unique constraints in IPAvailabilityRange

first_ip, allocation_pool_id and last_ip, allocation_pool_id
should be unique in the table.
These constraints are essential to detect concurrent modifications
of the IpAvailabilityRange table if the SELECT ... FOR UPDATE
lock is removed

Change-Id: Iaf2288c0b6bf27e93c03691073d7f505ef24fdd3
Closes-bug: #1373015

commit_message:
Rename doc environment to docs

As per the governance resolution https://review.openstack.org/119875,
projects should have a docs environment in their tox.ini testing
interface. Rename the doc environment to docs.

Change-Id: Ia375ab09ee7092711688f84112f7749f712b9848

subject: Fixing issue with API reconnection
messages:
[{'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 20:43:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 20:50:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/1/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/011df3d : SUCCESS in 41s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/1/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/cebee3f : SUCCESS in 48s'}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:40:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

API retries are great definitely needed. Though I have some questions about the implementation. 

Why slowly send old messages? Seems like premature optimization, send them in as fast as the api will take them, let the api slow down if needed.

Also possibly drop the max_retries altogether. If it fails log it, if needed get a new token, then the next post in 15 seconds will retry.'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:00:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:04:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/2/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/f8b35cd : SUCCESS in 50s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/2/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/df0db34 : SUCCESS in 36s'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:10:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As far as the send rate, it seemed prudent to throttle the number of messages being sent to the api.  Say you have an outage of several hours, every agent will have messages queued up and will send them.  When you only have 2 nodes like in mini-mon, yes it makes sense to send them in as fast as possible.  When you have 100's or 1000's of nodes trying to catch up, it could overwhelm the API.  That's why I made it configurable, so that if the user wants to send at the fastest rate possible, he can just set the backlog_send_rate to the same size as the max_buffer_size."}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:16:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I can see your point about the retries.  I was waffling on whether they were needed.  I guess with the message queue, we are no longer losing messages if the API is down, so we don't really need the retry logic.  I will remove it and post a new patch set."}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:34:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/3/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/6f88c8e : SUCCESS in 45s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/3/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/c096661 : SUCCESS in 1m 13s'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:54:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:58:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/4/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/192e313 : SUCCESS in 43s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/125776/4/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/8dc43b0 : SUCCESS in 39s'}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:46:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

My main point about the throttling isn't that is shouldn't happen but that the agent shouldn't do it, rather it should be done on the api end. There is no way for the agent to know if a thousand other agents are behind or if it is the only one. In each case you want a different behavior, the api on the other hand can throttle if it is overwhelmed or take things full speed if not."}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:50:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Looks like the log messages lost some info in the edit, not a big deal but would be nice to have.

I'm curious to know what others think, should the api throttle itself or should it be done by the UI?"}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:52:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12443, 'date': '2014-10-03 15:43:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I think the throttling mechanism is nice to have in the Agent.  I've worked enough network recoveries to value such an option.  Just ship with it disabled (where backlog_send_rate == max_buffer_size), which is what it looks like we're already doing here."}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-03 23:57:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-04 00:00:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Fixed issue in _post method and cut down on the amount of logging when queuing messages.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-04 00:01:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

commit_message:
Fixing issue with API reconnection

The agent had issues with the token when the API would go down and come back up again
Added a message queue to buffer metrics when the API was down or unreachable
Removed some excess logging of messages in debug

Change-Id: Ib1300bc0c66e00b06302b2b2f875f991520c9f1f

commit_message:
Use 400 instead of 422 for security_groups v2 API

For any invalid request format we should return 400, not 422,
this patch fixes this case for v2 security_groups API.

This patch follows the rule:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines

Change-Id: I78f523901918901e55b339d0cbd9cc78dd52044f
Closes-Bug: #1380456

What's the example where an extra = is needed here?

Also, like dean said, tests really needed here. Jump on #openstack-qa if you need some assistance with test strategy."}, {'account_id': 842, 'date': '2014-09-30 14:10:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sean, as per the current (Juno) nova.conf documentation (http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/list-of-compute-config-options.html) the example default value for the volume_drivers attribute are:

volume_drivers = iscsi=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtISCSIVolumeDriver, iser=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtISERVolumeDriver, local=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtVolumeDriver, fake=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtFakeVolumeDriver, rbd=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtNetVolumeDriver, sheepdog=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtNetVolumeDriver, nfs=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtNFSVolumeDriver, aoe=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtAOEVolumeDriver, glusterfs=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtGlusterfsVolumeDriver, fibre_channel=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtFibreChannelVolumeDriver, scality=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtScalityVolumeDriver

So picking the first item in the list as an example, without this change to lib/config if your local.conf contains:

[[post-config|$NOVA_CONF]]
[libvirt]
volume_drivers = iscsi=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtISCSIVolumeDriver

your $NOVA_CONF will end up with:

[libvirt]
...
volume_drivers = iscsi

In fact if you specified the complete example default value in local.conf you would still only see the above value for volume_drivers.

I'll amend my commit message text when I'm adding tests to make this more clear.

Fergal."}, {'account_id': 842, 'date': '2014-09-30 14:48:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-30 16:06:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-09-26 17:12:07.000000000', 'message': "local.conf processing doesn't handle '=' in values

When attempting to add a libvirt section with a volume_drivers entry
to $NOVA_CONF, via a post-config block in the local.conf file, I
encountered problems; the value part of a volume_drivers setting
is a comma separate list of driver=python.import.path.for.driver
values, but the post-config process chops off the value at the '='
so the $NOVA_CONF entry ends up as:

[libvirt]
volume_driver = driver

The fix ensures that complete value for volume_drivers is set
correctly in the $NOVA_CONF, by ensuring the '=' in values are
handled appropriately when processing the local.conf.

Change-Id: Id0cb1e6e1cece21bc5dbf427c4d756af86fbd927
Closes-Bug: #1374482
"}, {'created': '2014-09-30 14:48:52.000000000', 'message': "local.conf processing doesn't handle '=' in values

When attempting to add a libvirt section with a volume_drivers entry
to $NOVA_CONF, via a post-config block in the local.conf file, I
encountered problems; the value for this attribute takes the form

    driver=python.import.path.to.driver

but the value actually populated in the $NOVA_CONF was truncated at the
equals.

Taking the iscsi driver setting specified in the official nova.conf
documentation as an example, if I have the following in my local.conf
file:

[[post-config|$NOVA_CONF]]
[libvirt]
volume_drivers = iscsi=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtISCSIVolumeDriver

I will see that the generated $NOVA_CONF has the following:

[libvirt]
volume_driver = iscsi

This occurs because the existing handling for a post-config setion, as
implemented in merge_config_file(), splits the line on the equals sign,
and then uses the first and seconds elements of the resulting array as
attribute name and value respectively.

However when an equals occurs as part of the value this results in the
value being truncated at the first equals in the value.

The fix that I have implemented ensures that a complete value for
volume_drivers is set in the $NOVA_CONF, by joining the second and
remaining elements in the array with '=' to form an appropriate value.

I've also added test5 to tests/test_config.sh to test for an verify
correct operation when this scenario is encountered.

Change-Id: Id0cb1e6e1cece21bc5dbf427c4d756af86fbd927
Closes-Bug: #1374482

and then uses the first and seconds elements of the resulting array as
attribute name and value respectively.

However when an equals occurs as part of the value this results in the
value being truncated at the first equals in the value.

The fix that I have implemented extracts the rest of the line after the
first '=' character as the value and then strips leading and trailing
spaces from the value.

I've also added test5 to tests/test_config.sh to test for, and verify,
correct operation when this scenario is encountered.  Similarly I've
added test6 to ensure that trailing spaces in values are stripped
correctly.

Change-Id: Id0cb1e6e1cece21bc5dbf427c4d756af86fbd927
Closes-Bug: #1374482

commit_message:
local.conf processing doesn't handle '=' in values

When attempting to add a libvirt section with a volume_drivers entry
to $NOVA_CONF, via a post-config block in the local.conf file, I
encountered problems; the value for this attribute takes the form

    driver=python.import.path.to.driver

but the value actually populated in the $NOVA_CONF was truncated at the
equals.

Taking the iscsi driver setting specified in the official nova.conf
documentation as an example, if I have the following in my local.conf
file:

[[post-config|$NOVA_CONF]]
[libvirt]
volume_drivers = iscsi=nova.virt.libvirt.volume.LibvirtISCSIVolumeDriver

I will see that the generated $NOVA_CONF has the following:

[libvirt]
volume_driver = iscsi

This occurs because the existing handling for a post-config setion, as
implemented in merge_config_file(), splits the line on the equals sign,
and then uses the first and seconds elements of the resulting array as
attribute name and value respectively.

However when an equals occurs as part of the value this results in the
value being truncated at the first equals in the value.

The fix I've implemented, based upon review feedback, extracts the
contents of $0 before the first equals as the attr name, and extracts
the remainder after the equals as the value. Then it strips the leading
and trailing whitespaces from both as appropriate.

I've also added test5 to tests/test_config.sh to test for, and verify,
correct operation when this scenario is encountered.  Similarly I've
added test6 to ensure that trailing spaces in values are stripped
correctly.

Change-Id: Id0cb1e6e1cece21bc5dbf427c4d756af86fbd927
Closes-Bug: #1374482

commit_message:
Set Glance default_store to rbd in [glance_store]

Glance is moving from [DEFAULT] to [glance_store] for this option.
Since lib/glance sets both, let's also set it in both places for now.

Failing to do this causes g-api to fail to start with error:
"Store for scheme swift not found"

Change-Id: I9e33ababf7c51f5c750f90b8b366b9892bb4c8cd

commit_message:
Fix blocking reject rule for rabbit ocf

* Make RMQ unblock call safe (remove all discovered RMQ
  blocking rules, if there are many of them).
* Use unblock safe call prior to the blocking one.
* Make block call idempotent and add 5 retries for iptables.
* Add info log messages about block/unblock actions. Notify
  if RMQ blocking rule cannot be added for some strange reason.

Partial-bug: #1373569
Closes-bug: #1375824

Change-Id: I46c6bf3c83ada4273eaa05530e80886ebac7e75f
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Update openstack-doc-tools to 0.20

We need the new version to build the heat documentation in
openstack-manuals.

List of changes for openstack-doc-tools:

0.20
----

* ``openstack-doc-test``: Check for a ``\n`` in the last line of a file.
* ``openstack-dn2osdbk``: Properly handle internal references.

0.19
----

* ``openstack-doc-test``: Optimize translation imports, improve output
  messages.
* ``autohelp.py``: Improve sanitizer, better support for i18n in
  projects, allow setting of title name for tables.
* ``autohelp-wrapper``: Smarter handling of the manuals repo and
* environment
  setup, add support for the ``create`` subcommand.
* ``autohelp-wrapper``: Add support for offline/fast operation.
* ``autohelp-wrapper``: Add a module blacklisting mechanism.
* ``diff_branches.py``: Updated output format.
* Provide a ``hotref`` extension for sphinx, to automate the creation of
  references to the HOT resources documentation.
* ``openstack-auto-commands``: Handle python-openstackclient, handle
  python-glanceclient and python-cinderclient v2 commands.

Change-Id: I0a14023120e25af9b74eb62529f4090da0f56497

The failure on check-tempest-dsvm-full which e-r mistakenly attributed to 

https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1362347

actually looks like it'll be an issue. If you look at the failure logs for that run nova-agent invoked oom-killer:

http://logs.openstack.org/12/115212/5/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/11a1af6/logs/syslog.txt.gz#_Sep__8_12_10_46

It looks like running with the nova notification tests causes the nova-agent to exceed the node's 8GB of ram. I'm not sure the best way to address this, but I think we need to figure something out before we re-enable this test."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-09-09 09:25:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

a-ha, Matthew, ok... although I'm quite interested if that will be solved after yesterday infra discussions will find the solution. I mean the problem found by infra team that lots on unnecessary in most of the cases dependencies are installed on all the gate slaves eating kind of 30-40% of RAM on them (unfortunately, ZooKeeper among them :))

As far as I remember, one of infra cores proposed changes to remove these RAM consuming deps from the things to install on the slaves.

Will it be something useful?

P.S. this change did not fail the RAM before - it were successful job runs there... Dunno what actually changed till that time :-\"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-09 21:35:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

i take it this isn't directly related to this patch but a more common issue: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/045394.html"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2014-09-09 22:12:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@gordon: Well sort-of, it's not actually clear. Out of all the runs we've had in the last couple of weeks, this is the only run that's invoked oom-killer without neutron being enabled. Every other case of ram exhaustion has been a neutron job. Granted these are all still very infrequent, something here is causing a noticeable increase in ram consumption, albeit somewhat non-deterministically and infrequently.

Joe started that thread, because it's probably not just caused by ceilometer but a larger issue in the gate env. Dina is correct that Clark is working on removing things from the node which don't need to be running,(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119936/ ) like zookeeper. That in conjunction with decreasing the number of api workers should probably prevent this from happening again for a while. But, until the nodes are free of the unnecessary packages running this should be held. Honestly, I'm also a bit twitchy about adding anything ceilometer related to the gate at this point, because every time we do it breaks something."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-10 19:51:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Matthew. i'm fine with waiting for Clark's patch to clear up memory issue. that said, i think it's a little unfair to use ceilometer as a catch-all excuse for not merging. ceilometer afaik is always running on all tempest tests (capturing data and not breaking the tests)... the only difference here is a test is added to explicitly verify the data ceilometer collects.

from what i can tell the nova_notification test isn't incorrect (it seems to just create a server). can you confirm that the test is creating an instance as expected or is it creating an instance that is causing memory issues (ie. too large or not cleaning up)?"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-10 20:00:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Revert "Skip telemetry_notification_api test due to bug 1336755"

As https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114514/ has been merged, we can
try to check if changing of Ceilometer backend to the MongoDB makes the
situation better with running Ceilometer notification tests. Locally the
timeout issues were not reproduced both on MySQL and MongoDB, so this
change aims to check if the issue was solved by trying experimental runs
of MongoDB devstack Ceilometer testing.

This reverts commit 88004daa7b0fd746a60dd3b17d68ed4427b40e58.

Closes-Bug: #1276157

Change-Id: I41fce7e56a0e9fb111a95a266def786cb0f90c5e

Change-Id: I1b322b7e5dde7fd89f14447e65b2cf5dfd4ef900
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Horizon integration job: permissions

Trying to run Tox as is results in the following error on Jenkins runs:

py.error.EACCES: [Permission denied]: mkdir('/opt/stack/new/horizon/.tox',)

The tox command should explicitly be run with the stack user.

Change-Id: I1b322b7e5dde7fd89f14447e65b2cf5dfd4ef900

commit_message:
make  quotas decrease only once when deleting vms

delete a vm which vm_state is in soft-delete, should not decrease quotas again,
because instance in soft-delete vm_state hava already had quotas decremented.

Change-Id: I2471c66294abd46fd57c05b0dc5c3936d443d0d8
Closes-bug: #1333145

commit_message:
kill all processes when novncproxy stop

currently if novnc main progress stopped, children progress will not quit,
we should ensure all children progresses quit normally when main progress
stopped.

Closes-bug: 1329755

Change-Id: Id6506322b58685b81b03c477470ee05c5fa2bf04

Ok, I see understand what's happening better now.

The exception handler for the failed call to _delete_instance was calling _set_instance_error_state which calls _instance_update.

My patch fixes the bug that causes _delete_instance to fail which then avoids the call to _instance_update. That should be the better fix in this case since it fixes the underlying problem that caused the test to be slow."}, {'account_id': 8430, 'date': '2014-05-29 13:13:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 Workflow-1

Okay.. That's good information.  I'm not sure I completely agree.  Your fix does address the broken test case and should go first.  There is still an issue which is why conductor wasn't turned off via the use_local flag.  This is happening both in my setup and others.  Also your fix now leaves uncovered code which is better for the test case but bad from a testing/reliability perspective.  I'll do some testing and retool based on what I find.  Probably will add a test case to explicitly verify that path."}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2014-05-29 13:48:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2014-05-29 02:23:09.000000000', 'message': "Compute tests calling conductor and timing out

test_init_instance_stuck_in_deleting and
test_init_instance_deletes_error_deleting_instance verify we
call _delete_instance.  They also end up calling
_instance_update which calls the conductor.  However,
the conductor doesn't exist during unit test.  This throws an
exception, but only after waiting the mandatory timeout.

The change returns immediately via a mock and reduces the
test time from 10s of seconds to milliseconds.

Change-Id: I930ef0186ceee7ec4cb6d7eabe8ab08b8b7ed5e0

commit_message:
Compute tests calling conductor and timing out

For some passing tests we were calling conductor which wasn't set
to local.  This changes sets the use_local flag prior
to creating the compute.  This allows us to pass/fail faster
for test cases which exercise conductor calls.  This
follows the model of test_compute.py.

Change-Id: I930ef0186ceee7ec4cb6d7eabe8ab08b8b7ed5e0

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-06 21:34:33.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: spawn refactor - image validation descriptors

Adds field validation to the VMwareImage object via descriptor classes.

(This firt version of this was essentially extracted from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87002/34)

As much of the validation was not done prior to the refactor, this is
considered new functionality, so is split out for independent review.

TODO:

commit_message:
VMware: validation descriptors for VMwareImage

Adds field validation to the VMwareImage object via descriptor classes.

This is closely related to the spawn refactor work, since the first
version of this was essentially extracted from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87002/34.

As much of the validation was not done prior to the refactor, this is
considered new functionality, so is split out for independent review.

TODO:
Eliminate the heavy dose of hard-coded enums from model.py and look
them up dynamically.

partial-blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor

Change-Id: I1d2e07d013b78465b72a44303710d097716de03d

commit_message:
Change baremetal host mgr i/f before ironic merge

As part of the review of the ironic host manager code in the
ironic tree, prior to merging into Nova, it was identifed that
the 'host_state_cls' interface is not very intuitive.  This patch
proposes changing this interface so as to ease the refactoring of
baremetal_host_manager and the inclusion of the ironic_host_manager
as part of reviews http://review.openstack.org/#/c/103165 and
http://review.openstack.org/#/c/107316/

Change-Id: I4dde15126e785b4257ae195bd3132428fba92610

commit_message:
remove redundant brackets in set().

Using list comprehension for initializing a set will construct a list
which is used only once.Since what set() accept is a iterable object,
replace the list comprehension with a generator expression would be just
fine, and make the code faster and pythonic.

Change-Id: I50a9d6338d573b9681d9474aaeff166b97e93b0a

commit_message:
Add debug log for trust filter

Sometimes operator need information why the host doesn't pass
the check of scheduler, this patch adds information for trust
filter when the host can't be satisfied.

Change-Id: Ifc7b6fafc978feaf2f8424faf0b222e265d72310
Closes-Bug: 1301830

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

commit_message:
Software config hook for configuring with Chef-Solo

Write an in-instance hook which allows chef-solo to be used for
provisioning software on instances using SoftwareConfig and
SoftwareDeployment resources.
This patch replaces patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/80229/
which will be abandoned.

Change-Id: Ia7e884c5db138d83dcd67bce9361b46c66173401
Closes-Bug: #1279062

commit_message:
Always use jsonutils instead of json

Under Python 2.6 jsonutils imports simplejson, which
can not be used together with json. Using jsonutils
everywhere avoids the conflict. It also provides a
nice speedup (~ factor 40).

Change-Id: I38f4413019f33b0dd84917238709f103eba0b6d2

commit_message:
Correct the disk usage report in resource tracker

Currently the disk consumption of eph disk is based on
'ephemeral_gb' in flavor and instance; however, it's not accurate
because the eph disk is created based on user's input.
If eph disk is not specified, the eph disk will be created according
to the 'ephemeral_gb', if it's specified, the 'ephemeral_gb' will be
used as maximum eph disk can be created.
The patch get the real eph disk consumption and use it when doing
update for system disk.

Change-Id: Ie0c861c6c5860097190abc68a6b05a140d352aed
Closes-Bug: #1315988

commit_message:
Move bdms check early before create instance

There is a check in provisioning instances to validate bdms such as
eph disk + swap disk should not exceed eph disk size in flavor, no
more than 1 swap disk etc. This patch moves the check before
spawn instance, so spawn and destroy actions can be avoided if the
bdms is not valid for spawn.

Change-Id: I460fb29bb546999c0da8e11db22988ca93ccdd5b

commit_message:
Fix resume_guests_state_on_host_boot

Currently, during nova-compute restart, when
CONF.resume_guests_state_on_host_boot is set true, all existing
instances will be resumed. If there are any error, the instance
will be put into ERROR state. In the patch, we just leave the
instance in SHUTDOWN state. This way, we can directly run
‘nova reboot’ to get the instance back after errors got fixed.
With an instance in ‘ERROR’ state, one has to manually change the
DB record to other state before running ‘nova reboot’.

closes-bug: 1330583
Change-Id: Ifb2cc1fb96f47e74945ea6f1ed4d276d4e3adebc

commit_message:
VMware: Refactor wait_for_task to use looping call

Refactors wait_for_task method to use the LoopingCall the right way and
do away with creating an event each time. This also removes the need to
stop the loop on exception because that will be taken care by looping
call module.

Related-Bug: #1246848

Change-Id: Ic052b46fd0c3c926b7e4916405b903f366b4bfc4

commit_message:
Set root disk's size if it is a local image BDM

While preparing the block device mapping for creating new instance(s),
before sending the request to the manager, try to guess the size of the
root BDM if it is not set. The disk size will be taken either from the
base options (inherited from the instance type) or, if it is not present,
from the image size.

Change-Id: I05144bbf0cef8d69a6ca61b7d95561822a5cf886

commit_message:
Use oslo network utils function to set tcp_keepalive

In addition to the existing cfg option for tcp_keepidle, new values were added
for tcp_keepalive(to turn on/off this feature, tcp_keepintvl(to specify gap
between successive probes) and tcp_keepcnt(to specify number of probes). To
mimic existing behavior, tcp_keepalive defaults to True, and tcp_keepidle to
600(seconds). The other two default to None, and the oslo code will ignore
them unless specifically set.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia02adf410bbd214250eac42bfb42630631199b00

[{'created': '2014-05-28 12:19:39.000000000', 'message': 'Nova-compute cannot start if _init_instance failed

When we initialize service nova-compute, if there
were some error instances, the _init_instance
method maybe throw exception, then, the nova-compute
service would crashed. In my opition, no matter what
the result of _init_instance is, the nova-compute
cannot be killed. To fix this problem , I add the
try and except block to ensure the nova-compute
can run.

Change-Id: Ib687a9bde5a1c45450c3a9985f5504ab5c975cb6
Closes-bug: #1324041
'}]
commit_message:
Nova-compute cannot start if _init_instance failed

When we initialize service nova-compute, if there
were some error instances, the _init_instance
method maybe throw exception, then, the nova-compute
service would crashed. In my opition, no matter what
the result of _init_instance is, the nova-compute
cannot be killed. To fix this problem , I add the
try and except block to ensure the nova-compute
can run.

Change-Id: Ib687a9bde5a1c45450c3a9985f5504ab5c975cb6
Closes-bug: #1324041

commit_message:
Adds tty password entry for neutronclient

Added functionality from keystoneclient to fallback to the tty for password
entry if no password is given via the environment or the --os-password option.

Closes-Bug: 1356550

Change-Id: I7d0428a8901cae667ef598aa515e108a3a679540

commit_message:
handles keyboard interrupt

When an user intentionally provides an keyboard interrupt, neutronclient
throws the entire traceback on to the terminal instead of handling it.
neutronclient will now handle the keyboard interrrupt and provides an crisp
message on to the terminal.

Change-Id: I55a85cd4bfcbf26d81e5678b6f4aed3d1c288467
Closes-Bug: #1367283

[{'created': '2014-10-01 09:06:57.000000000', 'message': 'Correct 4xx/5xx response management in SessionClient

Currently SessionClient raises an exception when status code >= 400
unlike HTTPClient. neutronclient.v2_0.client expects HTTPClient
behavior.

This change disables exception raise when status code >= 400 in
SessionClient (more precisely in keystoneclient.session).

Change-Id: Ic96cb9326842f0b6a180fd8f94293da9fa0f6b2f
Closes-Bug: #1376171
'}]
commit_message:
Correct 4xx/5xx response management in SessionClient

Currently SessionClient raises an exception when status code >= 400
unlike HTTPClient. neutronclient.v2_0.client expects HTTPClient
behavior.

This change disables exception raise when status code >= 400 in
SessionClient (more precisely in keystoneclient.session).

Change-Id: Ic96cb9326842f0b6a180fd8f94293da9fa0f6b2f
Closes-Bug: #1376171

commit_message:
Use six.moves cStringIO instead of cStringIO

to keep Python 3.x compatibility, use six.moves.cStringIO to
replace StringIO

Change-Id: Ib6dcd06ca8c9342d26f3b7b738c99d23433d7f30
Closes-Bug: #1280964

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Use poll instead of threading.Event in heartbeat thread

poll() does not rely on absolute time.
This fixes an issue where the system clock may be changed, and
the heartbeat thread would stop heartbeating.

This also gives us flexibility to force a heartbeat in a later
change.

Change-Id: Ifde7b53f59788addc43a5dac95c7b6519d87e834
Closes-Bug: 1355375

commit_message:
Add a handle_delete method to SwiftSignalHandle

Swift containers and objects that were created by a particular
SwiftSignalHandle should be deleted when the resource is deleted.

Change-Id: Id9df03e139ca0632996f4f66c5f39e27bb04d1fb
Closes-Bug: #1379040

commit_message:
Change "healthmonitor" to "health monitor" in help info

Change "healthmonitor" to "health monitor" in help info for the
following commands:
   lb-healthmonitor-create
   lb-healthmonitor-delete
   lb-healthmonitor-list
   lb-healthmonitor-show
   lb-healthmonitor-update

Change-Id: Icbb219d9e4a2d88e00c5734acc30b1c7609d02fc
Closes-Bug: 1377516

commit_message:
Replace httpretty with requests_mock

The httpretty library has poor Py3 support, currently the only
working version is 0.8.0, all later minor versions are pinned.

Requests-mock library provides mocking layer for requests package. It is
written in such a way that it is fairly simple to convert existing
httpretty test suites to requests-mock. The library is hosted at Stackforge
and gated as usual OpenStack project.

Change-Id: If7f4baefb53976571efc47dda17a7b543112d555

commit_message:
Refactor cinder volume v2 API changes

The handling of name and description for v2 API is duplicated for
handle_create and handle_update methods. This patch defines a new
method which handles the differences in parameter names thereby
avoiding duplication and keeping the changes restricted to this
method to the extent possible.

Change-Id: I891aeea3fe5d7cb22be27e05ab72857af668e4ed

commit_message:
Fix to ensure endpoint_type is used by make_client()

This will fix an issue where neutronclient is ignoring the endpoint_type
passed to the client for v2 auth.

* make_client for '2.0' will now pass on the endpoint_type variable

Change-Id: I917ebee51254bc3e144f09573fa628d4ca192d13
Closes-Bug: #1368676

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

commit_message:
Allow unittest and build-app to use syslog

Provides a configuration option for operators to set the
syslog facility unittest and build-app will use.

To use syslog to catch the stage logs, one need only set
worker.task_log_dir to 'syslog'.

Change-Id: I94eff5eefd1c43a856226edb8d0c98f99f6d749e

commit_message:
SSL PKI

We need to be explicit about how our SSL PKI works. Outlining how we can
fit into existing PKI's and how we will auto generate keys for
developers.

There is also a patch which outlines some of the initial changes in
os-cloud-config I4d65cceee9e15ce0ca8ef309127a587135355810.

Change-Id: I32473fe797a4c1e28d14c3b82c8892c7c59a4e55

commit_message:
Use real script for copying files over

The current commands in tox.ini fail if there are no files to copy over.
Let's use instead a proper script that takes care that some files
actually exist.

commit_message:
add kubernetes volumes to glance pod

Use kubernetes volumes for data storage rather than placing data
directly on the container filesystem.  That provides a starting point
for thinking about persistent data -- one could replace the emptyDir
source with an explicit path via hostDir, and then you would have
storage that would persist over a container delete/re-create.

Change-Id: Ifade1cb2ba546e5e0207c3d8c84965dc2195716b

commit_message:
keystone pod needs KEYSTONE_DB_PASSWORD

if we want to be able to run multiple keystone container instances, the
password cannot be generated as part of the container boot process; it
must be passed it as part of the pod template.

Change-Id: Idd1b50b6bdb3788eec316bf22fb954f5ecbaa4be

commit_message:
glance images need keystone password

glance keystone password cannot be generated during container boot
because we need the same value in both the -api and -registry
containers.

commit_message:
Add is_int_like() function

Some OpenStack projects (like Cinder, Ironic, Nova) have similar
is_int_like() function so it's would be nice to keep it in common
code. oslo.utils seems to be the proper place for this.

Change-Id: Ieb76a32e8ad9fe80bbb8ce9d1c4860a594a2893e

commit_message:
Add flavor-from-sysmeta-to-blob spec

Flavor data is currently stored inefficiently in system_metadata and
should be moved to being stored as a blob in an appropriate place
per-instance. This will facilitate storing additional flavor details
that we badly need, such as extra_specs.

Change-Id: I4a06d6c0ff3b9db0b3bde17e78afad1a4de1457a

commit_message:
Support Cinder API version 2

Add support for the second version of the Cinder API, which brings
useful features such as scheduler hints, more consistent responses,
caching, filtering, etc.

Available volume services (such as 'volume' and 'volumev2') are
discovered at run time when creating the Cinder client.  Consequently,
there is not need for deployers to make a choice between API version 1
or 2, because the newest service is automatically chosen.

Implements: blueprint support-cinder-api-v2
Change-Id: If9eedd446e017a2f2a4e1b3257ff0d04834f9603

commit_message:
Migrate tox to use testr

This patch moves all unit tests to use
testr as the test runner. This means all
tests need to be subclassed from unittest
to be discovered by testr

Change-Id: I9b0e782be87ea2b5db72b56ddad1d239a83e9ee3
Closes-Bug: #1330204

commit_message:
Update image building steps in software-config README

dib-run-parts script used by diskimage-builder was moved to a
separate repository which has to be fetched and added to PATH.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow

Update hp3parclient and add new feature

Add Retype a volume to supported operations for Juno.

commit_message:
Publish cliff and stevedore docs on openstack.org

The cliff and stevedore docs previously lived on readthedocs.org, but
the builds there are not working because our doc build depends on some
things we cannot configure to run there (we don't get to inject our own
conf.py).

This commit turns on the publishing jobs for those libraries for
docs.openstack.org. We will turn off the rtfd.org jobs after we have the
new copies publishing and we update the references in the package
metadata that point to the documentation.

Change-Id: I1c9f788f61675c6720292cff00245d7f1a0c4977
Closes-Bug: #1374073

commit_message:
add kolla-common shell library to base image

This adds a /opt/kolla/kolla-common.sh to the base image as a place to
put commonly used functions.  The goal is to avoid code duplication
across all the images created from this base image.

Change-Id: Ib670fe369bb8048aa69979b74a984fa4ddaae7d9

[{'created': '2014-10-12 20:54:35.000000000', 'message': 'Closes-Bug: 1379513

Previously the glance-base script did not configure the registry
host IP. This causes API to try connecting to registry on
localhost. Since registry is bound to MY_IP, api is unable to
connect to registry. This change adds support for the glance-base
script to configure the registry_host parameter in api.conf to
MY_IP.

Change-Id: I1c711ff8aa95abec5ca306f03bd7e0a3883ca578
'}]
commit_message:
Closes-Bug: 1379513

Previously the glance-base script did not configure the registry
host IP. This causes API to try connecting to registry on
localhost. Since registry is bound to MY_IP, api is unable to
connect to registry. This change adds support for the glance-base
script to configure the registry_host parameter in api.conf to
MY_IP.

Change-Id: I1c711ff8aa95abec5ca306f03bd7e0a3883ca578

If you want to change the default value for PUBLIC_IP to be GLANCE_API_PORT_9292_TCP_ADDR that would be fine, but it is expected right now -- since kubernetes does not provide any external ip management natively -- that you may want pick the value of PUBLIC_IP yourself.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-09 20:36:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Lars,

Thanks for your feedback. I noticed how the PUBLIC_IP is being used elsewhere in the start script. I don't understand how the PUBLIC_IP works for the keystone public url in the endpoint-create command? Keystone is populated with the PUBLIC_IP which is not reachable by other containers. In my deployment, other OS services are unable to connect to the public url of glance. I would think that we want to use the proxy ip for all 3 glance keystone url's."}, {'account_id': 8745, 'date': '2014-10-10 13:18:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In general, we would like the InternalURL endpoint to be accessible to other containers, but we want the PublicURL endpoint to be something that will be accessible from *outside* of the Kubernetes environment...and in the medium term, this will be something managed outside of Kubernetes (in the short term it's not managed by anything, and in the long term we hope that kubernetes develops the ability to manage external addresses).

This implies that (a) it will probably be different from the internalURL (and the adminURL), and that (b) it will probably need to be passed in as part of the pod configuration."}, {'account_id': 6836, 'date': '2014-10-10 21:30:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-10 21:34:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Closes-Bug: 1379442

Previously, the glance-api start script would use the container
IP instead of the proxy IP for the public url when creating the
keystone endpoint. This causes keystone to provide an unreachable
IP within the public url and other OS services are unable to
connect to the public url.

Change-Id: I44befc84a90f59d535a951ee81aaff0fa1ba952d

commit_message:
Use beaker to do acceptance testing of Puppet

Re-submission of 102071.
Requires ruby 1.9, which is easy to get by requiring trusty. The
beaker tests will install puppet latest from packages.

Change-Id: I05fd0a949755a727063c79b6b602e048b4148505

commit_message:
Update cinder content for Juno

I updated the cinder content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Partially restructured procedures to improve consistency
   and flow. Future patches will fully address general
   improvements.
2) Fixed Identity service configuration options.
3) Removed extraneous message broker configuration options.
4) Configured "my_ip" option on all distributions.
5) Added workaround for packaging bug on Ubuntu.

This patch originates from testing on Ubuntu only.

Change-Id: I61bbc1c13a24698973bbd0fb9a3ae00a4cd99f71

commit_message:
Allow file_upload_temp_dir override

This adds the ability to overide the
file_upload_temp_dir setting in django
which is usually '/tmp' by default but
may not be appropriate for all installations

Change-Id: I1cd1be8285e9fb53b2e269b4b34cbd9ff336ba37

commit_message:
Change to use monasca everywhere

Change packages from com.hpcloud.mon to monasca.api

Rename service from mon-api to monasca-api. Move config file
to /etc/monasca, jar to /opt/monasca

Renamed files from mon- to monasca-

Use the monasca group.  Required so API can write to
/var/log/monasca and read config file in /etc/monasca

Change user from mon_api to monasca_api

Change-Id: Idaefe138629595507f3d38a533381408cc6f32e3

commit_message:
Added ATHORIZED_KEYS into settings.yaml

We have two types of ssh keys:
1) system which is from /root/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
2) user defined which is set by user via web interface

Cobbler during provisioning gets user defined
ssh key from provisioning data (come from nailgun
provisioning serializer) and system ssh key directly
from /etc/cobbler/authorized_keys.

Image based provisioning is implemented as fully
data driven process. So we need system ssh public key
to come inside provisioning data and to make nailgun
able to put this key into provisioning data we need
to have this key in settings.yaml.

Besides there is a PR to fuel-library. This patch is
about putting system ssh public key into settings.yaml
during master node deployment. For details see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127158/

Change-Id: If3d44903cb8f1ca6636041905dc269edf5088494
Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Closes-Bug: 1378832

commit_message:
Add __init__.py for nova scheduler filters

To use these filters out of tree right now, you have to specify them in
nova's available_scheduler filters by full path. But in order for the
modules to be found and loaded, you must have an __init__.py.

Closes-Bug: #1357878
Change-Id: I4816d9dbe0e93056792fad48e6228ffdd531e346
(cherry picked from commit 87aac8823b468a7bb80c994cd207ec5df66163c5)

commit_message:
Display proper missing argument name

Find and show argument name instead of showing argument of 'dest'
Add functional test for this
Remove test_cli_utils.py -> utils.py because this actually utils,
not tests.

Change-Id: Icc138ecf40b4929826efcad52c135c8809348d20
Closes-Bug: #1380562

Think about keystone-specs, openstack-manuals and openstack-doc-tools: We currently include them but should we really? For openstack-manuals and openstack-doc-tools, I really like the automatic syncing of requirements but both are kind of developer repos.

commit_message:
updated requirements repo readme

The purpose of the requirements repository, it's history, and
consistent review guidelines are something that's currently lore
passed down through the ages.

We should write this stuff down, and come up with consistent
guidelines for submitters and reviewers to get us all onto a single
page wrt reviewing and acceptance criteria.

Change-Id: I72f0f5771fee637d0b651d76217ce3959a4b92b7
