This model seems similar to another area that I've encountered before, there might be some interesting overlaps and learnings that can be shared. It might be to much research like but you might be interested in reading about artificial immune systems.

http://www.cs.unm.edu/~immsec/publications/gecco-steve.pdf (or just search for artificial immune systems) has a good little overview of what they are.

If you consider a engine as the 'immune system' that receives inputs that cause reactions (immune responses) and the immune system tries to protect itself from those inputs (convergence toward a healthy immune system) using adaptive mechanisms/responses (taskflow workflows could be called t-cells) then there starts to become an interesting similarity between convergence and AIS ideas.

Might just be something to think about/look over (could be useful shared ideas that you can use)."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-06-30 17:06:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-30 17:06:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

One other comment.  While detecting infrastructure level failure of a Compute instance is nice, it is by no means enough.  Often the problem can not be discerned through the Nova API, the problem is that the software on the Compute instance has gotten into some useless state even while the instance continues to run.  We need an architecture where application-level failure detection, as well as infrastructure-level failure detection, can create the need for some healing action.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-07-02 15:52:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Convergence Specification

The is the top-level spec and design for convergence.  There are
subsidiary specs:

(1) Convergence observer, at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96394/
(2) Convergence engine, at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96404/
(3) Convergence continuous observer, at
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100012/

Specifies bp convergence
Co-Authored-By: Mike Spreitzer <mspreitz@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I51f071e8fa93171395021e5f78ac8f4861e1ef62

Hi Dina,

Just a question/thought overall for these docco patches. As there is a Configuration Guide in the OpenStack Manuals, my plan is to get rid of these configuration options (contained by ceilometer.conf) in the developer guide, I did not have time unfortunately to do it so far. So my opinion is that the OS Manuals guide should be checked if it is consistent with the current state of the code, and if yes, than add a reference to it here and keep in sync that one. What do you think?

Best Regards,
Ildiko'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-10-13 12:19:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ildiko, actually I don't know for sure. your variant looks like nice solution for me as well - but really I started all this thing with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127909/ change - I just wanted to add conf option, but there was no needed section, so I just cleaned a little bit most ugly moments. If you'd say we'll need to wait this syncing of development guide, it's ok as well - as said, all this small clean-up is related to the things I found during working on just one change. What's your opinion here? Do we need more consistent doc right now?"}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2014-10-13 12:32:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The reason behind my plan is to avoid the duplication of work and effort on syncing multiple documentations. I'm not against merging your patches, as you've already done the work with it. But if you agree with the base idea, then I will create a bug for cleaning this up and do it asap, before we would have more rounds on this area.

So if we agree, then IMHO, if you're finished with this activity, then let's merge it and I can use it as a baseline, if not, then let's stop here and I will use your updates and finish with this activity in the Config Guide. (Of course if you would want to finish this activity, I will not steal it from you, I think we can agree, if this would be the case :))

What do you think?

Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-10-13 12:42:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
NSX: drop support to deprecated dist-router extension

The NSX plugin originally implemented its own 'dist-router' extension.
During the Juno timeframe the DVR extension was introduced and the NSX
plugin was ported to support both. At the same time 'dist-router' was
marked for removal in Kilo.

Now that Kilo opened, we can drop the deprecated one.

Change-Id: I7d6d2524ef6d5cb94a9e8514425a1a288eea7210

commit_message:
Check config default value is correct type

Given a type of Opt, check that the default value supplied to the Opt is
of the same type as the Opt.

E.g. cfg.StrOpt('user_attribute_ignore', default=99) will log a warning
as the default is not of type string.

Closes-Bug: 1261792
Change-Id: I12cd5f4be82ac5ed0ebb348b358dd8eaf04e4e0d

commit_message:
Bump eventlet dependency to 0.15.2.

Eventlet 0.15.2 introduced the set_hundred_continue_headers() method
on eventlet.wsgi.Input, and Swift needs this method for erasure-code
support.

Change-Id: I6a8211373936b6f4bf256b537edf64e77ab7a7ae

commit_message:
Rebuild the hot-ref with new IDs

This patch uses the content generated with a new version of dn2osdbk.
All the docbook IDs have been changed, and are not prefixed with the
source file name. This should not be a problem since this guide has not
been officially released and is not linked from the docs index page.

Change-Id: Ie781bd340428bf1f56f7c4dcb80ea506de4ba8f3

commit_message:
Remove outdated examples

The examples directory contained a lot of examples written for version
1.0.  The examples do not work with the latest version of the client, so
this CR removes them to avoid confusion.

Change-Id: Ie421bb2a28c73b4b7ce2236af19d86216112af05

commit_message:
Fix consistency between Order/Secret/Container

Order/Secret capitalized factory methods disappear and are replaced
by more appropriate get/create methods in their respective managers,
to match the revised Container code.

The higher level REST functions for get/get_raw/post/delete become
private so that the namespace for developers using the client is
much cleaner. For example, nothing is visible in the top level
client object besides the manager classes for container/secret/order
and nothing is visible inside the manager classes besides the
appropriate get/create/delete methods (or other applicable
functions).

Internally, the barbican_cli code uses at least one private property
from ContainerManager, but it is assumed to be OK since it is within
the same "package", and the code will be maintained simultaneously.

Change-Id: I89525506f3be26b77421a5b8efa49bb645169aaf

commit_message:
Improve the deployment's creation and deletion

1. When a deployment creation fails because of schema validation error,
an exception should be raised, the deployment status should be changed
to 'deploy->failed'.
2. When a deployment creation fails because of schema validation error,
users can never destroy a deployment, also because of validation error.
This patch ensures that users could always be able to delete a deployment
successfully.

Change-Id: I7dea64da19e4d4ba4302f0270e524c584f43d65d
Closes-Bug: #1368484

Ceilometer username fixed

* replicaset configured properly in case without slaves

commit_message:
Add PyMySQL to global requirements

Theres is a single MySQL connector in a global requirements, so there is
a sense to add one more, at least for py3 testing. Let it be PyMySQL.
PyMySQL is a pure-Python MySQL client library. It hosted on PyPi [1],
licenses by the MIT license, python3 compatible, and seems to be
developing [2].

[1] https://pypi.python.org/pypi/PyMySQL
[2] https://github.com/PyMySQL/PyMySQL/commits/master

Change-Id: If3daeb4559ee3fd7fa69ea654f223ecd13b99cc8

from puppet log

commit_message:
Remove broken 70-generic kernel as well as 70-virtual

Some vendor specific images have both -virutal and
-generic kernel images, so we need to remove both versions
of the troublesome -70 kernel so that we can install -69
and let openvswitch build.

Change-Id: Id6bdbefbf6fd3b783a189c1cf2ca0923ac5c43df

The store module is removed from glance project and new glance_store
module is created, but the glance project code was not updated
properly for the required changes.

_get_from_store and _get_size methods raises store.NotFound exception
from glance_store but not caught in the glance api.

Closes-Bug: #1380552
Change-Id: I7b79d6ceb0de56f921418e9c19d2305115167ee6
'}]
commit_message:
Fix for adopt glance.store library in Glance

The store module is removed from glance project and new glance_store
module is created, but the glance project code was not updated
properly for the required changes.

_get_from_store and _get_size methods raises store.NotFound exception
from glance_store but not caught in the glance api.

Updated exception.NotFound to store.NotFound which returns 404 NotFound
response to the user.

Closes-Bug: #1380552
Change-Id: I7b79d6ceb0de56f921418e9c19d2305115167ee6

Reduce duration of some long-running tests

This patch reduces the duration of some tests related to Redis and Mongo
so that developers can get faster turnaround on feedback when testing
locally or waiting on the py27 gate.

commit_message:
NetApp fix for default host type in eseries

This fixes the issue where the default host type
provided in mapping should be high performing LnxALUA
type for eseries. It also makes it configurable in case
users want to configure a different host type.

Closes-Bug: #1365884

Change-Id: I30992ca69c25c3c02334470aae90c32731a5f3f4

commit_message:
Fix error response for FixedIpAlreadyInUse

The server create code doesn't handle FixedIpAlreadyInUse and
ends up returning a 500. This handles the exception and returns
a 409 to match PortInUse.

Also moves the v2.1 exception to use a conflict as well for
consistency.

Change-Id: Ia3a03ecc821e4fc8a244191c439fcfafb628b9a3
Closes-Bug: #1379533

What you're actually doing here is instructing accessbot to grant meetbot the ability to change channel topics in #puppet-openstack, which is almost certainly not what you want. Instead you should add the channel to the channels list at http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/config/tree/modules/openstack_project/manifests/eavesdrop.pp#n39 (assuming what you want is for meetbot to log your channel discussions).

Meetings should instead take place in one of the meeting channels (#openstack-meeting, #openstack-meeting-alt, #openstack-meeting-3) so that people who want to participate in your meetings don't have to be in your project-specific channel to do so."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-13 16:40:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add yasfb for making RSS feeds in docs

We are adding an RSS feed to the oslo-specs repository using yasfb
in https://review.openstack.org/120194

This is a documentation build-time dependency, and not a runtime
dependency for OpenStack.

The library isn't tested under Python 3, but I don't foresee any issue
with it working and we don't use Python 3 for building documentation
from Sphinx.

Change-Id: I3d5df90d77a5826c2e5ed463dc957a5477bb3478

commit_message:
Add Admin doc for an Introduction to Manila

Add doc for an Introduction to Manila dealing with the fundamentals and basic
terminology used with respect to Manila from an Admin perspective.
Also, create a directory for an Admin ref along with a sample index.rst.

Change-Id: I1847f291750227927a747b5ea224a6861310a529

commit_message:
change db host prevents creation of db and users

When changing ['openstack']['endpoints']['db']['host']
to anything besides 127.0.0.1, the openstack-db recipe
fails to create databases and database users. I believe
this is due to MySQL bind-addess equals
['openstack']['endpoints']['db']['host'] and the root user
not having permissions from that address.

changed host variable for mysql to localhost if info['host']
does not equal localhost in db_create_with_user() method

Closes-Bug: #1333691

Change-Id: I3cf919a56068f4d3144e2bedb4debae14589dd66

commit_message:
Add check for makemessages in tox.ini PEP8

This commit adds a check of extracting message catalogs to
tox PEP8 check. It is useful to avoid a bug like bug 1379054.

It also fixes a warning "WARNING:root:No local_settings file found."
in run_tests.sh --makemessages and --compilemessages by specifying
Django settings.

Closes-Bug: #1379507

Change-Id: I5541e28a87d48601202bf8180a18eadb5a91770b

messages:
[{'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-09-02 18:16:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-02 19:44:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build succeeded.

- check-tripleo-novabm-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/26/118426/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-novabm-undercloud-precise-nonha/a05b87d : SUCCESS in 40m 41s
- check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/26/118426/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha/23d5785 : SUCCESS in 51m 50s
- check-tripleo-novabm-overcloud-f20-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/26/118426/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-novabm-overcloud-f20-nonha/003f255 : SUCCESS in 1h 28m 14s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-ha http://logs.openstack.org/26/118426/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-ha/b6767c0 : SUCCESS in 1h 15m 20s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-02 20:06:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/26/118426/1/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/afeb90e/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 50s'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-09-09 01:53:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This seems fine, as far as it goes...

My only objection would be that I don't think it goes far enough. It requires the user to provide details of the gerrit server for each run; it only applies patches one at a time; and although it does update the local checkout of the repo, that doesn't change what ends up on images - without sitting the DIB_REPO_* variables correctly, DIB will still be pulling the raw repository from upstream.

Ordinarily I'd be in favour of waving this through as it's better than what we have already and we can work on the rest later; but in this particular case we happen to already have a tool that does all the things I'd like this one to do.

Specifically, see https://github.com/jamezpolley/tripleo-end-to-end/, where I've been working on taking the prep_source_repos tool developed by adam_g and lifeless for use managing our CD servers and worked on making it into a packageable tool.

This tool works on a YAML config file rather than requiring the server etc to be specified each time. The YAML file can handle multiple projects, and multiple patches per project. Once it's done, it drops a shell script with all the DIB_REPO_* variables that instruct DIB to use the locally-patched repos rather than upstream.

I *think* the only work remaining here is to get it set up as an openstack project. 

I'm leaving my vote here as no score; I don't feel like this patch needs further work before it can be merged, but at the same time I also think it would make more sense to work on getting prep_source_repos available as a package rather than going live with this tool and then switching to a new incompatbile tool shortly afterwards."}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2014-09-12 06:08:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This looks okay, I have some concerns about some parts of the code, which I've not published, because I agree with James. We have the temprevert stuff in toci which is different again, and prep-source-repos which is already in use in our CD clouds today, so I don't see value in a competing solution."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-09-17 20:36:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The code has some issues that would need to be cleaned up, and I think based on the previous comments on this that the general approach requires more discussion.'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-10-13 16:58:34.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

When I last looked prep-source-repos was wip and didn't have a means for pulling latest patchset.  Now it does it looks a little better.

@james - multiple gerrit change ids can be specified on the command line and all are downloaded and applied to whatever repo they are destined for, so I don't understand why you say that only 1 change is applied?

Also - set-source-vars already exists in tripleo-incubator/scripts, which sets the correct vars based on local checkouts, which is why I didn't reimplement that here."}]

Change-Id: I44b65da085c986df873f88009373c57de78cafe6
'}]
commit_message:
Add script to patch repos from gerrit

Given a set of change ids, cherry-pick those changes into local
directories so that set-source-vars can be used to build with that
set of changes.

Change-Id: I44b65da085c986df873f88009373c57de78cafe6

commit_message:
Use strutils from oslo.utils

Rather than sync'ing with oslo-incubator, let's use the library
oslo.utils instead. Removing the local copy of strutils.

With removal of strutils in local, gettextutils is now safe to
remove as well.

Change-Id: I0d98d41b03d105e34933efcdb5c60020141e13fb
Partially-Implements: blueprint improve-oslo-usage

commit_message:
Optionally upload stage logs to Swift

Adds a mechanism for selecting an offload service
for stage logs once a unittest or build task is
completed. The first example mechanism is Swift.

Adds a table to illustrate the 1-to-many relationship
between an assembly and these logs.

Change-Id: Idc3896b5f8e9c44909e829b7ea998c593d994038

commit_message:
Sync oslo-incubator for fileutils, log and policy

Sync from oslo-incubator commit 4504e4f4917d99c4889a8a5b7907d6b23ced2ffc

Additional changes:
- remove excutils since this already moved to oslo-utils
- added _i18n.py workaround from oslo-incubator, required while transitioning
to oslo.i18n
- fix openstack_dashboard/policy.py to work with latest policy code

Change-Id: I904b9af517cc85e0cc041a1467d6fda599d8d3a1
Partially-Implements: blueprint improve-oslo-usage

commit_message:
Updates to horizon settings.rst

Added documentation for auto_fade_alerts.

Also added to the OpenStack section documentation for:
OPENSTACK_API_VERSIONS,
OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_MULTIDOMAIN_SUPPORT,
OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_DEFAULT_DOMAIN,
OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_BACKEND,
CONSOLE_TYPE,
TROVE_ADD_USER_PERMS,
TROVE_ADD_DATABASE_PERMS.

In the Django section, added ALLOWED_HOSTS
and a note about use of SECRET_KEY.

Closes-Bug: #1221115
Change-Id:  I16596fef2af62b892cef00ab25e2bfe4a80e1c65

commit_message:
add action file that is created via test_dump_loads test

The test_dumps_load tests creates the following file:
    congress/policy/tests/snapshot/action
in the source tree. This commit adds this file to the source tree
so it's no longer hanging around after the tests run.

Change-Id: Id92481eb3e30216d7219b9aaa20e5f575f170d8b
Closes-bug: #1379627

commit_message:
Sync with latest oslo-incubator to add uuidutils

This patch syncs congress with oslo-incubator from commit:
   4dec8601c71f0574a92d7ead13752f030db1779c

And makes the necessary changes to congess to integrate the changes
mostly around the removal of gettextutils from oslo-incubator.

Change-Id: I6e216791e7d882fcbcf21fdd5752f66126ff5530

commit_message:
Fix F812 PEP8 error

One file was redefining a variable, thus exposing this PEP8 error:

    F812 list comprehension redefines 'n' from line 1868

This fixes it and enables the check in tox.ini.

commit_message:
Enable H305 PEP8 check

Fixes files with the PEP8 error:

    H305  imports not grouped correctly

and enables the check in tox.ini.

Import order is: stdlib, 3rd-party, project imports

Change-Id: I81fc67bc9f79c514b6f4941a13e44c95badd34e2

@Sergei,

I'm not sure it is the correct way, since the first positional argument is 'message': https://github.com/stackforge/rally/blob/master/rally/exceptions.py#L46

If we pass a string in the 'message' argument to the constructor, then it will be used as the actual message, instead of being a part of a larger message: https://github.com/stackforge/rally/blob/master/rally/exceptions.py#L89.

But I think the second option is preferable."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-07 15:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix messages in rally exceptions

Many exceptions in rally.exceptions contain "%(message)s" in their msg_fmt
attribute. When raised with message="...", however, these Exceptions just
assign the passed string to the message attribute instead of formatting it
with msg_fmt.

We fix this issue here and also refactor a bit the scenario classes:
* Remove the unused InvalidTaskConfigException;
* Move the DummyScenarioException to the dummy bechmark scenario module;
* Move the Tempest* exceptions to the corresponding modules

Change-Id: I551f38edd5ec7bc67dd952a2203508f64c4b2518

commit_message:
display boolean and json parameters in stack launch form

Horizon fails to render boolean and json parameters properly in the
stack launch form, instead of rendering these fields it renders a
duplicate of the previous field.

Change-Id: Idb2fcf4b52578951fb578138a80529eefc140d1a
Closes-Bug: 1360495

commit_message:
Add missing parameters to Client's docstring

Client's constructor receives keyword arguments (**kwargs), which are
then passed to an HTTPClient. Since HTTPClient receives numerous
parameters, Client's docstring describes which parameters are expected
and their meanings. This patch adds 2 parameters which HTTPClient
receives but weren't previously documented in Client's docstring.

Change-Id: I12e520f6e26c3aa7c76b190c3e2125d77c71a19a

commit_message:
Enable H307 PEP8 check

Fixes files with the PEP8 error:

    H307  like imports should be grouped together

and enables the check in tox.ini.

For the modified files, made sure the import order matches the
template as described in:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#import-order-template

This order is currently: stdlib, 3rd-party, and project imports.

Change-Id: I4538356c207535b778da1273aadcf3b4a7b20383

commit_message:
Port floating_ip_pools extention to v2.1

This patch ports floating_ip_pools extention from v2 to v2.1,
and have v2 unit test cases shared between v2.1 and v2.
Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I0b34358db08a29e76a59b22a0992abc88296058d

commit_message:
Add external_network_bridge parameter to the L3 configuration

Because openSUSE uses 'external_network_bridge =' by default in the
l3_agent.ini configuration file we should ensure that external_network_bridge
used the correct value (br-ex).

Change-Id: I3911b01f3618825fe46e20d9a61f8df3022f51b8

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-22 07:07:12.000000000', 'message': 'Correct protocol/action initial values provided to UpdateRule

Currently protocol/action initial values in UpdateRule are incorrectly
formatted: neutron returns lowercase protocol/action strings but
UpdateRule form expects uppercase strings as initial values which
implies to reorder protocol/action choices to select the right initial
values.

This change corrects initial values provided to UpdateRule which allows
to remove the trick in UpdateRule.__init__ and initial protocol/action
values become translatable.

Change-Id: I7145dd591581a7e5e3fb0591518d0e1564f38c10
'}]
commit_message:
Correct protocol/action initial values provided to UpdateRule

Currently protocol/action initial values in UpdateRule are incorrectly
formatted: neutron returns lowercase protocol/action strings but
UpdateRule form expects uppercase strings as initial values which
implies to reorder protocol/action choices to select the right initial
values.

This change corrects initial values provided to UpdateRule which allows
to remove the trick in UpdateRule.__init__ and initial protocol/action
values become translatable.

Change-Id: I7145dd591581a7e5e3fb0591518d0e1564f38c10

commit_message:
allow empty device name when launching an instance

From comment 9 on Nova bug 1337821, the device name should be optional
and can cause issues if we force the user to select one and they enter
an incorrect value. We should make the field optional (and make sure
we still create the instance correctly in these cases.)

Change-Id: I7745b67bc52bbfbb98aa223b6e14ae2f96d81339
Closes-Bug: 1339760

[{'created': '2014-10-08 11:27:02.000000000', 'message': "Fix error status for get_from_manager method

commit_message:
Fix error status for get_from_manager method

Parameter 'error_statuses' is processed as a list type, but in heat
utils it's a string value. As result Failed stack will never be deleted.
In this patch error_statuses is changed to expected list type.

Change-Id: I3fa1def29e0afa7a808a58cd1e806360f35f5f9d

commit_message:
VMware: prevent race condition with VNC port allocation

When spawning some instances, nova VMware driver could have a race condition
in VNC port allocation. This fix ensures that the lock is done on the
actual setting in the VM configuration spec.

Co-authored-by: Marcio Roberto Starke <marcio.starke@serpro.gov.br>

Change-Id: I70fab021bbf2df418df53e5f47e19cf16dbe45ac
Closes-bug: #1357372
(cherry picked from commit 948ff4f3d0a159f1aed9fab65d205ede845b3eb9)

commit_message:
check the configuration eqlx_cli_max_retries

we need to to check the value of the configuration item eqlx_cli_max_retries
in the code in order to ensure the "eqlx_cli_max_retries" is equal to or
greater than 0

DocImpact: The 'retries' is not a configured number of attempts
Change-Id: If9fadda83a855b4bbda6129d3b3a64d296eb2b54
Closes-Bug: #1372454

commit_message:
Breaking test dependencies from enviroment variables

One test ('test_get_client_all_creds') will fail if any of the typical
Openstack environment variables have been set (eg OS_PASSWORD).

Change-Id: I91d7a61d794e0648c7a8b64affa29cb14248e98a
Closes-bug: #1376247

commit_message:
Remove templates from toctrees

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

Change-Id: I83398908e48668c90906cf40ca104178f6f7896e

commit_message:
Fix account rc files creation for Swift users

Id02ebdfa5cb3f6c763293876c6bb031184ebd663 introduced a small
regression which makes the command x509-create-cert fail with
'ERROR (CommandError): Invalid OpenStack Nova credentials.' for
Swift users.

The handling of specific password for Swift users was introduced
in Ifb57a43aad439ffe041e98465719a8a8eceae544

Change-Id: I3f328b1358bad0bdf7056796eabfe846dd5bae3a

endpoint in the service catalog.

An interesting idea.  In my experimental code, I've been doing this, which spins until mysql is up and running:

    while !  mysql -h ${MARIADB_SERVICE_HOST} -u root -p${DB_ROOT_PASSWORD} -e "select 1" mysql > /dev/null 2>&1; do
        echo "waiting for mysql..."
        sleep 1
    done

What do you think, does it make more sense to spin inside the start script, or just exit and have kubernetes reschedule?'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2014-10-09 01:18:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I have a preference to exiting, that way the script is deterministic and idempotency will ensure a correct operation.  Your approach is also fine, as long as we get something merged, I don't care because keystone is busted as is :)

Regards
-steve"}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2014-10-09 09:46:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

larsks indicates he has something to resolve this issue in his queued patches'}]

commit_message:
Make keystone cycle until mariadb is avialable

If mariadb is not available, keystone implodes on startup and
never exits.  Because it doesn't exit, k8s will not restart the
container.  With this change, we exit early if mariadb is not
available.

Change-Id: I3b09c620e458b6d3e145805e5852ad3714cad770
Closes-bug: #1379057

commit_message:
correct various issues with glance images and configs

- update keystone endpoints/user on boot (to avoid problems caused by,
  e.g., a stale password or invalid endpoint urls)
- require GLANCE_DB_PASSWORD and GLANCE_KEYSTONE_PASSWORD in the
  environment, since we start multiple containers

Change-Id: I31214b81280ed34409f92e79003c1116d5737d2e

commit_message:
NetApp fix eseries concurrent vol map failure

This fixes the issue while mapping volume to host
when the requests are very close in time proximity.
The map operation has been synchronized.

Change-Id: I2e120d84d3b96faa4ab8d4324e70a089bcddeaa5
Closes-bug: #1312685

commit_message:
NetApp fix attach fail for already mapped volume

This patch fixes the error raised during mapping of a volume
to the host during attach operation if the volume is already
mapped to the host.

Change-Id: I4f711e7ac18eea0dfddab65fd85a3601fe967a88
Closes-bug: #1310659

Something that I do not completely get yet:

(1) Are the plug-ins allowed to modify the stack? If yes, what parts can they modify? If not, should some code be added to restrict modifications?

@Thomas Spatzier, @Angus Salkeld,
Yes, the intent of the referenced blueprint is to provide providers of cloud services with a simple way to extend the top level stack lifecycle operations with provider-specific custom code. 

@Thomas Spatzier, 
The cleanest approach would be to not allow changes to the stack parameter(s). Since this is cloud-provider-supplied code, I think that it is reasonable to not enforce this restriction, and to treat any modifications of the stack parameter(s) as a defect in the cloud provider's extension code. 

@Thomas Spatzier,
re "Would each plug-in be invoked for each stack operation? Or would it make sense to declare the operations when a plug-in should be invoked per plug-in?", the action code is being passed to the provider-supplied code, which could then decide what to do. Also, if a provider class replaces only one of the pre and post operations in the base class, the base class will do nothing for the other method. My feeling (which could be wrong) was that this was sufficient and that adding additional declarations would increase complexity with no significant gain.'}, {'account_id': 8435, 'date': '2014-05-29 02:37:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-29 02:37:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Implements stack lifecycle plugpoints

Stack lifecycle plugpoints have been proposed in
http://summit.openstack.org/cfp/details/86
and
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/juno-summit-heat-callbacks

Implements: blueprint stack-lifecycle-plugpoint
Change-Id: I8c7b5d0113392e54fe0f35933c2c10da277fd90b

StaleElementReferenceException occurres when accessing web element that
was reloaded but looks the same. It happens for example when trying to access
form under Project/Data processing/image registry -> register image. It
is ussually caused by javascript that is loading the page or by mistake
in script logic.

This patch wraps the WebDriver and WebElement classes and catches the
occurrence of StaleElementReferenceException and tries to find the web
element again. Till maximum limit is reached or top element is reached
as this suggest that mistake was made by programmer.

Closes-Bug: #1353342

commit_message:
Add workaround for StaleElementReferenceException

StaleElementReferenceException occurres when accessing web element that
was reloaded but looks the same. It happens for example when trying to access
form under Project/Data processing/image registry -> register image. It
is ussually caused by javascript that is loading the page or by mistake
in script logic.

This patch wraps the WebDriver and WebElement classes and catches the
occurrence of StaleElementReferenceException and tries to find the web
element again. Till maximum limit is reached or top element is reached
as this suggest that mistake was made by programmer.

Closes-Bug: #1353342

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I8e24e952e0fb81bed21b7139870d6d7506509c93

commit_message:
Clarify snapshot deletion methods

There are two similar and confused things presented in code:
'handle_delete_snapshot' and 'handle_snapshot_delete'. In this patch
documenatation is updated to clarify current differences between this
two features.

Change-Id: Idfdb91b698b27652940e0d544d34210b80aaae43

commit_message:
Commit transaction on object delete

The postgres gate jobs currently have an intermittent failure
where a deleted resource shows up in the resource list.

This change does a transaction commit on object delete, which
brings delete behaviour in line with soft_delete behaviour
(soft_delete uses update_and_save, which also commits).

Change-Id: I5e1be4c197863fde3149c964f992ad816db88b7e
Closes-Bug: #1370865
(cherry picked from commit 146a734555207583b4ca9b20e1f101c5f467a28f)

commit_message:
fixes stack deletion failure, when vol in deleting

when an delete operation is requested on a stack, and the volume in stack
is already in 'deleting' state, heat fails to delete the stack and goes to
DELETE_FAILED state instantly.

Instead of going to DELETE_FAILED state instantly, heat needs to safely
wait for the volume to complete its deletion process, so that heat can
then go ahead and complete stack deletion successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1362708

Change-Id: I088eab90bee4bc804abe9e505fd61b17b266def1

Use import_module instead of try_import so that any import exception
includes a full stack trace and the original error message.

Change-Id: I64449688f22a224b590807317472f26e64f377a3
'}]
commit_message:
Improve error reporting for backend import failures

Use import_module instead of try_import so that any import exception
includes a full stack trace and the original error message.

Change-Id: I64449688f22a224b590807317472f26e64f377a3

commit_message:
Publish Config Ref and Install Guide for Juno as well

Copy over the Config Ref and Install Guide to juno locations until
we branch of Juno.

Add juno/index.html page - but do not add external links to it yet,
let's first see that everything works fine.

Change-Id: I3a2533a4d25659860e6578cd84b15fa82dd3c269

commit_message:
Remove @author tags from copyright statements

We have git to track the authorship of files. It is not necessary to use
the @author tags in the copyright statements.

Change-Id: Ib99e53323dba7315a6c8cf73ba4c7eb7c9803ac3

commit_message:
dn2osdbk: handle internal references

The internal references were not properly created. This patches make the
:ref: inline markup create a <xref> tag when the reference is internal.

This patch also reworks the sphinx extension to handle the URLs that
will be generated in the hot-reference with the new :ref: behavior.

Closes-Bug: #1378073
Change-Id: I84bf268dc1055dc6b39f23c4415734184ec57eec

commit_message:
Ironic: no need to call instance.save() in spawn

The commit bceb6342994fc9d38a51a19e5b07652a5fdfd503 had an
unnecessary call to instance.save in the spawn method. This
is not required as instance.save is called after the spawn
method to update the instance in the database.

This save a database call.

Change-Id: I8b65c2de67bdb556c8eeacb12bfa64807efecaef
Closes-bug: #1366694

commit_message:
Don't update a LoadBalancer under autoscaling control

Unfortunately, Autoscaling currently uses the update() method of a
LoadBalancer resource to do updates, with the result that the current
member list gets persisted (good) and used to compare in the event of
future *stack* updates (bad).

With this patch, we assume that LoadBalancers under the control of
Autoscaling will never have a members list property supplied in the
template.  We then ignore any updates to Autoscaling LoadBalancers that
don't actually modify the template.

The test changes revert the changes made in order to be able to merge
d32370233eaf2a5c32888f269bd1dc5e0e787467, before which LoadBalancers were
behaving correctly.

Change-Id: I9c02ab3d3dfbee0a8a90dd0ba345a5acdaf8a610
Closes-Bug: #1379619

commit_message:
Unit test of 55-heat-config

This implements a unit test of the os-refresh-config script 55-heat-config.

The test does the following:
- hook-fake.py is a fake hook which is executed for every config item
  found by 55-heat-config
- test_heat_config.HeatConfigTest does the following:
  - creates a temp dir and copies hook-fake.py into it for every
    hook/group name the test expects (puppet, script etc)
  - writes our sample config json and invokes 55-heat-config
    to trigger the execution of the fake hook for each config item
  - assert that the fake hooks wrote out the expected json for each
    config item

Change-Id: I87c108dc07dacde767b7f74c82c7ae06ab765738

commit_message:
Added AUTHORIZED_KEYS field into settings.yaml.erb

This is for making it possible for nailgun to pass
default (aka system) public key into provisioning data
so as to put them on a target node apart from user
defined public key.

Related PR to fuel-web is
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127490/

Change-Id: Id5dff61444d7dfb278e0ae6c49b0f772ff68ffd6
Closes-Bug: 1378832
Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning

commit_message:
Fix apischema for boolean_string

Reasons:
 - apischema for boolean_string should relay on existing
   `boolean` type instead of `integer`

Changes:
 - updating apischema;
 - fixing unit tests for configuration API controller

Change-Id: Ifb12dc5190de3f173cba34780db5b3547faa2219
Closes-Bug: #1377231

commit_message:
Use masks in release orchestrator_data

Since Fuel Upgrade feature, it's a common practice to add new
openstack release, so it'd be very useful to add new release
with a kind of macro replacement in paths to repos and puppets.

Since this commit, the macro replacement for MASTER_IP was
introduced.

Change-Id: Ie3a79ab105461f10cbabcc5353ca952946200f32
Closes-Bug: #1378901

commit_message:
unlock VLAN Manager radiobutton from Network tabs

Now nova-network works properly in VLAN Manager mode. But element on UI
for setting this mode currently locked. It will be unlocked by this patch.

commit_message:
rest: allow to use timespan to define archive policy

Users can now use a timespan to specify an archive policy, which makes
it easier to define what one might actually want to retrieve as users:

POST /v1/archive_policy
=>  {"name": "foobar",
    "definition": [{"timespan": "1 day", "granularity": 5}]}

<= {"name": "foobar",
    "definition": [{"timespan": "1 day", "granularity": 5, "points": 17280}]}

Change-Id: I121a7c307c93b2ffc8e65f681b62d61a70b7cbd7

commit_message:
Re-organize juno specs

As discussed on the latest sahara meeting, we've decided to re-organize
specs to have the following two categories:

 - approved: things we approved but didn't implement
 - implemented: things approved and implemented

Current change doing it for Juno specs, except Kilo and client.

Change-Id: Idcf55ca37a83d7098dcb7c2971240c4e8fd23dc8

commit_message:
Add waiting interval and retries for Glance

Glance backend launch may takes up to 1 minute
and without this changes will failed falsely.

Change-Id: Ie5dfb2ce54b64d6092915599567aa1144cb34b6a
Closes-Bug: #1376198

commit_message:
Use --no-recommends when installing SUSE neutron packages on compute/network node

It does not makes sense to install rabbitmq-server and couchdb on the compute
or network node. Use --no-recommends to not install recommend packages.

Change-Id: I6ebe7c974160abd7208c5fc7e1be38b2068c21ef

commit_message:
should not set wsgi_socket_prefix

The per-platform setting of wsgi_socket_prefix has been moved
into the Apache module - horizon should just include ::apache::mod::wsgi
Add a dependency on the version of puppetlabs-apache that sets the
default wsgi_socket_prefix for osfamily RedHat

Closes-Bug: #1374634
Change-Id: Iba8311ba25445d3367e71d3c0e854291c33e7258

commit_message:
Examples that test scaling across AZs

These examples exercise the support for spreading scaling groups
across availability zones.  See
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116139/ for the change that adds that
support.

Change-Id: I17e49c9437f3e6f28c1e79036aa477c95b3f7fbf

commit_message:
Fix exception handling on test_delete_nonexistent_volume

test_delete_nonexistent_volume wants to check the exception would be
received when nonexistent volume was specified. But currently, this
test case checks the exception would be received when nonexistent
metadata was specified.

Change-Id: Ia110618d5c658551a1826d495656954be02f4326

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-10-10 19:43:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

Please take a look on https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages to be sure how to write the commit messages. Also although I'm ok if you'll fix this, you probably noticed, that this bug was assigned to other person. If bug/BP is assigned to someone, it's kind of really unpleasant thing to reassign it without making sure that assignee is ok with it. If you want to fix something, please assign it to yourself first."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-10-10 19:53:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

A-ha, btw, this bug really firstly was assigned to Nelly (unofficial) to make her first contribution easier :) i did not know the exact bug, so when Lena asked me if she could fix this unassigned one, of course I was ok :) Nelly, please always assign the bugs you're planning to work on to yourself. This is really helpful!"}, {'account_id': 13518, 'date': '2014-10-10 19:59:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Edit docs for docs.opentack.org/developer/

Add missed steps in the installation process for running tests.
Mongodb and libmysqlclient-dev packages need to be installed for
Ubuntu12.04 and mongodb and mariadb-devel.x86_64 (or .i386)
need to be installed on Fedora20.

This information has been added to:
doc/source/contriburing/source.rst.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1368974
Change-Id: I163879498b37866c8679b7f69ba60abaacc2e017

[{'created': '2014-10-06 12:47:40.000000000', 'message': "Introduce NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer

Neutron attributes serialization is moved from NetworkManager to
NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer.

commit_message:
Introduce NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer

Neutron attributes serialization is moved from NetworkManager to
NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer.
Versioning is introduced in NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer.

The previous code in network/neutron.py checked specifically for 5.1
environments. This caused 5.1.1 environments to fall back to the
old behavior and set network_type to 'flat' and configure 'physnet'.

(cherry picked from commit 069849284a7c50cf3cb957c9b9392c45c6fc6675)

Change-Id: I3940d0910c888794f82dd2159727ef5073367916
Closes-Bug: #1357298

commit_message:
Pass correct 'security_groups' value for port operations

Make sure pass the correct value of 'security_groups'
property to neutronClient for OS::Neutron::Port resource
operations.

Change-Id: I84fa2c149c18b0b85be7cf1ff5a8ab2641a5c276
Closes-bug: #1369933

commit_message:
Bump required openstack-common version dependancy

This patch bumps the version of openstack-common required to 10.0.3
as this version adds the attributes required to set the internal
endpoints that were added earlier.

Additionally this updates the test suite to perform a more though check
of the settings that have been updated by this bug.
It will first check that identity-internal is being set individually as
it, by default, share the same settings as identity-api.
Following this the registartion is checked that the variables coming
from openstack-common are correct as to not break the existing check of
this nature.

Change-Id: I5398ca45bbdf5ec43e9da5d89300bfb15a4b806e
Closes-Bug: #1356732

commit_message:
[DOC] Add notes on disabling permissions for Data Processing

In order to use Sahara from Horizon in the case where Sahara is
not registered with keystone, the service-based permissions on
the Sahara panels must be removed.

Change-Id: I5936ae6862c24ce8bfe7b55318234c1f4bae7925
Closes-bug: 1379906

commit_message:
Remove and deprecate dashboards config from settings file

Dashboards are now configured via the pluggable dashboard/panel
mechanism and the order can be specified in the pluggable config.
On the other hand, we have HORIZON "dashboards" and its tuple order
overrides the order specified in the pluggable config.
It is confusing to be able to configure the order of dashboards
in two places, and we no longer need to have "dashboards" config
parameter in settings.py and a sample local_settings.py.

* If HORIZON_CONFIG contains "dashboards" and update_dashboards
  is called, a deprecation warning will be displayed. It is useful
  to warn operators to change OpenStack Dashboard settings.

* HORIZON_CONFIG "dashboard" parameter itself still works and
  there is no chnage in the behavior, so it is a safe change
  and have no upgrade impact.

* This change also removes default_dashboard from settings because
  it can be configured via pluggable dashboard config too.

After removing "dashboards" config, the order of the dashboards
are now controlled by the order of openstack_dashboard/enabled and
"Identity" dashboard is displayed before "Settings" dashboard
in the navigation menu.

commit_message:
Remove deprecated use of gettextutils import _

The initial hacking check I wrote allowed users to check in code
using 'from cinder.openstack.common.gettextutils import _' or
'from cinder.i18n import _'.  This was to ease the transition for
code that was in flight with the old import.

Now that we have moved Cinder over to using cinder.i18n and most
of the code that was in flight with the old import has been merged
and/or fixed, I am updating the hacking check to enforce the use of
cinder.i18n and fixing the cases that still had the old import.

Change-Id: Iff6ccac1996c06bbc5defd5139113a2baa0b677c

commit_message:
Increment minor version to 10.1.0 for bugfix

As the bugfix to cookbook-openstack-identity added new attributes, thus
it is considered a new "feature" and thus it needs a greater version bump.

Change-Id: I8e6b1c53e209eb27bf0cbed922ae99b457f99d29

[{'created': '2014-10-11 00:24:50.000000000', 'message': 'Fix rebalance crash post-2.1.0 upgrade.

If you had a builder file from an earlier version of Swift (before
6d77c37) and you attempted to rebalance it with a new version of Swift
(after 6d77c37, before this commit), you could get a crash.

Commit 6d77c37 changed the calculation for parts_wanted slightly
(round up instead of round down), so if a rebalance is attempted
without recomputing parts_wanted, then swift-ring-builder crashes.

The crash only occurs if the first command run is "rebalance". Adding
a device, removing a device, changing a device's weight, or changing
replica count (basically, anything that gives you a reason to
rebalance) will all cause parts_wanted to be recalculated, so
subsequent rebalances will succeed.

Change-Id: I6f7a69701f74546a00d3183aa7763e9e708408c9
'}]
commit_message:
Fix rebalance crash post-2.1.0 upgrade.

If you had a builder file from an earlier version of Swift (before
6d77c37) and you attempted to rebalance it with a new version of Swift
(after 6d77c37, before this commit), you could get a crash.

Commit 6d77c37 changed the calculation for parts_wanted slightly
(round up instead of round down), so if a rebalance is attempted
without recomputing parts_wanted, then swift-ring-builder crashes.

The crash only occurs if the first command run is "rebalance". Adding
a device, removing a device, changing a device's weight, or changing
replica count (basically, anything that gives you a reason to
rebalance) will all cause parts_wanted to be recalculated, so
subsequent rebalances will succeed.

Change-Id: I6f7a69701f74546a00d3183aa7763e9e708408c9

commit_message:
Add graduated oslo code to requirements

This is the first step of the oslo usage cleanup.
The patches to clean-up the local copy of oslo code
will be submitted separately.

Change-Id: Ic59275e78478c328517960f010095b86f0030402
Partially-Implements: blueprint improve-oslo-usage

commit_message:
Remove 'links' section from several v3 Identity objects

The links field in the returned objects from the v3 Identity
API aren't really useful, so let's remove them.
Managed to remove most of them from the core API.
I'll likely remove the extension/contribution (oauth/federation)
related ones in another patch.

Also in this patch the code for setting services and projects
was changed. Though not incorrect, it was not needed to copy
the entire returned object, we should just need to pass in
the fields we want to update.

Change-Id: I164ca9ad8b28fa10b291e9115ef40753e387c547

commit_message:
Add setup/cleanup_instance_network_on_host for nova-network API

When reschedule/unshelve/evacuate/rebuild instance, the instance
is moved from one host to another. The network should be updated
for the instance. And there are similar APIs
migrate_instance_start/stop, those two APIs should be used for
migration case as the name. So adds new APIs used to update
network resource when instance is moved.

This patch implements new APIs for nova-network API

Change-Id: Ia734f9f04f6fc7efc2884325b595df8ab57b45d8
Related-bug: #1327124

[{'created': '2014-09-10 14:46:59.000000000', 'message': "Work around keepalived split brain

When a host reboots, it's possible for keepalived to come up whilst
the host's network is still being reconfigured (which happens
asynchronously). This can cause the netfilter it puts in place to
fail to see announcements from other members of the cluster,
convincing it to bring up the VIP when it already exists on another
host.

The approach here is crude: every five minutes we cause a reload of
keepalived's configuration, which has the side-effect of making it
reappraise its netfilters and regenerate them.

commit_message:
Work around keepalived split brain

When a host reboots, it's possible for keepalived to come up whilst
the host's network is still being reconfigured (which happens
asynchronously). This can cause the netfilter it puts in place to
fail to see announcements from other members of the cluster,
convincing it to bring up the VIP when it already exists on another
host.

The approach here is crude: every five minutes we cause a reload of
keepalived's configuration, which has the side-effect of making it
reappraise its netfilters and regenerate them.

This is a stopgap measure whilst the underlying causes are bottomed
out.

Change-Id: Ic0397d79465869b78a72faef8653aedee321a3e2
Partial-fix: 1367742

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

I have made most of the changes suggested. 

After speaking with the ansible devs, the ansible-playbook CLI is meant to be human-readable, not for API consumption and the only way to write out a single json file containing all the output values for the playbook would require 'screen scraping' all of the output, and writing it to a custom file.

The other option is writing a custom Logging callback and installing it on each box, with an ansible.cfg that points to the custom Logging callback script.

Neither option seem very appealing though..

-Steve Gregory"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-28 19:04:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Software-config hook for ansible

Added ansible to the software-config README

Created a new folder elements/heat-config-ansible that will be
pre-installed by diskimage-builder on any images wishing to use the
ansible hook.

Created an example ansible heat template with an example ansible
script as a starting point.

Updated README.rst to reflect how heat-config-ansible interacts with the HOT template.

Change-Id: I861e96186e2f5d5b65ea5100edf1b82e753c425c

commit_message:
Sync process utils from oslo

This patch backports the missing change to fix ssh_execute password leak

------------------------------------------------
The sync pulls in the following changes:

105169f8 - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages (SSH)
-----------------------------------------------

Closes-Bug: 1377981
Change-Id: Ie0caf32469126dd9feb44867adf27acb6e383958

commit_message:
fix dependency between ml2 configs and package

debian platform missing a dependency between the package that installs
ml2 plugin (neutron-server) and the ml2 plugin configs
(neutron_plugin_ml2) on control node. neutron_plugin_ml2 can only be
ensured to present after the package installation.

the dependency only apllies to node where package neutron-server is
installed (control node) as this plugin class is not linked to
neutron-server.

Change-Id: I20dd5481527ea007779129eafc1558f328ca375a

commit_message:
Change eth0 to eth2 in Ops Guide Networking Diagram

1) Built a new version of figure 12.2 replacing eth0 with eth2
and clearing up shape overlaps from the original diagram.
2) Changed references to the internet facing eth0 to eth2
in the text corresponding to figure 12.2.

Change-Id: Iedbcb1de123627158a67dd97e820158d844be9f2
backport:none
Closes-Bug: #1372516

[{'created': '2014-10-12 16:15:08.000000000', 'message': "Update neutron content for Juno

I updated the neutron content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Reinstated the 'neutron-db-manage' database population step
   because the RC2 packages required it.
2) Explicitly removed 'connection' options on network and compute
   nodes because the default configuration on some distributions
   reference a SQLite database that could cause problems.

Change-Id: I663b4effbc52071de2783d3c4018cc970b5fb14b
"}]
commit_message:
Update neutron content for Juno

I updated the neutron content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Reinstated the 'neutron-db-manage' database population step
   because the RC2 packages required it.
2) Explicitly removed 'connection' options on network and compute
   nodes because the default configuration on some distributions
   reference a SQLite database that could cause problems.

Change-Id: I663b4effbc52071de2783d3c4018cc970b5fb14b

commit_message:
Add support for argparse Namespace objects

The Namespace objects returned by argparse contain all defined options
even if they are unspecified and default to None or ''.  Also it
is not iterable.  Change all that to add only the options presented
to argparse to the cloud_config.

Change-Id: Ia22fad60c81ab0b2878b404c0c8608d903ca964b

commit_message:
Add share network id field in share server info

In share server responce in manila api only information about
share network name is exist. But name can be different. That's
why separate field with share network id is added.

Change-Id: Iac429a2d38f9565239d08d57a8f6cece696124a1
Closes-Bug: #1378687

commit_message:
Use 'generate_request_id' func from common code

There are two reasons to use it:
1) Removal of duplication
2) In Python 3, webob will return bytes, so we need to fix
'generate_request_id' func so that it also returns bytes.
The behaviour is unchanged in Python 2.

Partially implements use-common-code

Change-Id: I4627e290c0b5c71fcfdbd1f88c5f592385bdd4f5

commit_message:
Add info to generic driver doc

Add known restriction to cDOT driver doc, that says:
- Juno version does not use security services data provided with share-network.
  These data will be just ignored.

Change-Id: Idf118242fbe9a6e6be44a243cd1aac8e34cc1227

Enable H702 PEP8 check

Fixes files with the PEP8 error:

    H702  Argument to _, _LI, _LW, _LC, or _LE must be just a string

and enables the PEP8 check in tox.ini.

commit_message:
Add support to Devstack to run with ML2 SR-IOV NIC Switch MD

The following variables should be set in Devstack local.conf configuration file:
        Q_PLUGIN=ml2
        Q_MECHANISM_DRIVER=sriovnicswitch
        Q_AGENT=sriovnicswitch
        The PCI_PASSTHROUGH_WHITELIST variable will set the "pci_passthrough_whitelist" value in nova config
        E.g PCI_PASSTHROUGH_WHITELIST='{"address":"*:07:00.*","physical_network":"default"}'

Change-Id: Ic8894e5adc365bbf22e6cd25a491830a815ac220
Signed-off-by: Omri Marcovitch <omrim@mellanox.com>

commit_message:
No longer stripping dots from downloaded filenames

Previously, the filename (which comes from our database
that validates the filenames at store-time) was
being passed through defaultfilters.slugify and that
was removing dots from the filenames, which was
undesirable.  Also added a unit test for this.

Change-Id: I4fccf2c3e065be1c1ae3826ab5d4bded359db251
Closes-Bug: #1379455

commit_message:
NSX: update_lswitch method can add duplicate version tags

The nsxlib.update_lswitch() method automatically appends the neutron
version as a tag to the lswitch. Because of this it's possible to have
this same value added many times which exceeds the number of tags
nsx allows which results in throwing an error. This patch fixes this
issue by adding a new method to remove old version tags on the lswitch
which is called in update_lswitch()

Change-Id: Ibf37284aaa3f414fb512389f4ea687974ffafc64
Closes-bug: 1355424

when using a swiftclient. This implementation isn't great as there

commit_message:
Try to keep an open connection swift

Reduce load times by removing the need to reauth against keystone
when using a swiftclient. This implementation isn't great as there
is no neat way of keeping a connection object. The generator methods
should probably be refactored into a class at some point, but for now
we'll use a method to establish a new connection or get an existing
one.

Change-Id: Ie9dc339341b13ba672dfcebf9ab5c66f94246ff4

commit_message:
Add support for command line argument processing

Now takes the ability to pass in a dict of key/value pairs, probably
from a command line processing thing like argparse, and to overlay them
on the config that came from the files or env vars.

Change-Id: I830699476e2340389979b34704c0dfbfe97a1e08

commit_message:
Handle the project/tenant nonesense more cleanly

devstack clouds are more strict that public ones, so it's more important
to get project_name vs. project_id correct. Solve it with brute force.

Change-Id: I957b19c23266d379834361ab6a5b3b2dc5d15d3d

commit_message:
Add cache control settings

Things need to do local caching, which means they need to control
some settings about that. Add simple cache settings support.

Change-Id: I7b56cc25ebe7a803816d95b79d0329f8e42025ba

commit_message:
Revert "Relocate volume to compliant datastore"

Commit 4be8913520f5e9fe4109ade101da9509e4a83360 introduced a regression
which causes failures during cinder volume re-attach. This patch reverts
commit 4be8913520f5e9fe4109ade101da9509e4a83360 as an immediate fix.

Closes-Bug: #1379830
Change-Id: I5dfbd45533489c3c81db8d256bbfd2f85614a357

commit_message:
Support Cinder availability zones

Add a new 'volumes_availability_zone' option for node groups, that
enables creation of volumes in a specific Cinder AZ.

Change-Id: Ia17d1628c7d5d06f0924edc8f92a0d26fff143e0
Implements: blueprint support-cinder-availability-zones

commit_message:
Convert migrate reqeusts to use joins

The modifications to add joins for fixed_ip_requests allows us to
condense three network calls into one for both start and finish
migration.

Change-Id: I61ca03661f722c6406d39021b79a648f4374dfcd
Partial-bug: #1365606

queries look good, this is the idea'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-25 02:38:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Why don't we use database views for read-only queries like this with lots of joins?  Does it buy us anything besides cleaner code?"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-25 16:28:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

here are the drawbacks with views:

1. the application is no longer given the choice for how to compose the FROM clause for a particular query.  if a new situation comes along where we don't want some particular join present or don't need those columns, the performance overhead is now permanently built into the view, unless we build a *new* view to suit that use case.   This is complex and won't be very apparent to developers.

2. The view is opaque; people mistake the views for tables and then join to *them*, killing performance in a big way.   this is in some ways an extension to #1.

3. migrations can be made more complex

4. migrations are more frequent as new queries needed to be supported by the application must now be designed twice, once in the app and a second time as an appropriate view-based construct.   again another extension to #1.

5. SQLAlchemy's eager loading API is not designed with pre-joined views in mind; while it isn't incompatible with them, every query against a view that pre-joins would need contains_eager() to ensure those additional columns are not wasted."}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-09-25 18:09:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-25 18:19:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

@Michael, thanks for the reply, it was really a question for my own education.  I worked on a project as a co-op and the guy that wrote most of the DB code was view-crazy, which was easy to code against, but it was not a project where performance was a priority.'}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-09-25 18:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-25 18:25:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

@Matt - yeah, I came from a view-heavy shop and those were the problems we had, mostly that it was a big deal to change views or add new ones and we tended to overuse the ones we had.   I wrote SQLAlchemy with the idea in mind that we can keep the SQL fluency on the app side while not requiring lots of long SQL strings and redundant code.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-25 21:13:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use database joins for fixed ips to other objects

Many of the fixed ip related calls are extremely inefficient. This
joins a couple of calls so that we can optimize queries that use
them.

Change-Id: Ifa2e4c6ac517286f7ae952052d29801b45a6b6b2
Partial-bug: #1365606

commit_message:
Finish objects conversion in the os-interface API

Most of the API code was using instance objects already except for the
listing, so this updates that.

Updates the test to use a fake instance object rather than a dict to
enforce the change.

Also adds a note on the slightly weird call to common.get_instance
in the show method when the instance isn't used for anything, it's
really a check to make sure the instance exists.

Part of blueprint kilo-objects

Change-Id: Ief17c57afbd81e2b6aef9586b448e8797aaa6544

commit_message:
Port cloudpipe extension to v2.1

This patch ports couldpipe extension from v2 to v2.1,
and have v2 unit test cases shared between v2.1 and v2.
Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Id40c637c0fc207e97b1d094805eb0cee6e9cd9c9

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-20 11:26:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

As mentioned previously I think this runways concept is overly bureaucratic process for the problem we actually have. 

All the problems listed in the doc would easily be address by simply maintaining a list of all blueprints numerically ranked by priority order & periodically updating that ranking as suits the changing environment. With a clear priority lists reviewers can use tools to query gerrit for reviews with associated priorities. The idea of artificially restricting what core team can go around approving for merge, when the code is ready & posted, is crazy. It is not respectful of my own ability to best prioritize *my time* or working practices to suit the workload I have to deal with, nor does it make efficient usage of the contributors time to artificially delay their work if someone is willing to review it.

IMHO this proposal is symptomatic of the (flawed) idea that we can (or should) run nova as a top down, tightly controlled project where leaders go around telling people what they must be working on at any given time. That is the model of closed source development, not the way to create a healthy open source project where contributors feel valued IMHO.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-08-25 18:37:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-08-25 18:39:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

(We're really lacking a good way to link conversations that span gerrit and the mailing list)

Some thoughts from me on this: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/042860.html and http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/042866.html

I think Eoghan does a good job of explaining why this kind of control mechanism is not something to be adopted lightly http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/042762.html

 One thing I'm not seeing shine through in this discussion of slots is
 whether any notion of individual cores, or small subsets of the core
 team with aligned interests, can "champion" blueprints that they have
 a particular interest in.

 For example it might address some pain-point they've encountered, or
 impact on some functional area that they themselves have worked on in
 the past, or line up with their thinking on some architectural point.

 But for whatever motivation, such small groups of cores currently have
 the freedom to self-organize in a fairly emergent way and "champion"
 individual BPs that are important to them, simply by *independently*
 giving those BPs review attention.

 Whereas under the slots initiative, presumably this power would be
 subsumed by the "group will", as expressed by the prioritization
 applied to the holding pattern feeding the runways?'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-27 09:59:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I largely agree with Dan.  Prioritizing a list based off rough consensus seems good enough without adding this additional "layer" of process.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-09-25 09:24:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

So maybe we should turn this conversation around...

* I think we have good agreement on there being some project priorities.
* we have good examples of what needs a spec+blueprint, and what doesn't, and have a more sensible line there

What we really need to look at is, do we want lots of low priority blueprints, or do we want to be more honest with the submitter, saying, no this just will not fit in the release?

Now, lowing the blueprint bar, I would hope a large number of those low priority blueprints will go away all together, and just go into the general pile of code to review.

In addition, if we can engage everyone in the priority setting process, I hope that more nova-core types will be bought in an aligned with the priorities, so we are likely to do a better job of reviewing the blueprints with higher priorities.

So... here is an alternative idea... We start using the exception process, getting core reviewers to sign up for blueprints to get into kilo-3, so basically we have a soft feature freeze at the end of kilo-2, making kilo-3 much harder to get into, leaving more time in kilo-3 and the RC window for bug fixing. We can get core reviews signed up to the high priority goals, so they are able to take on features that need that time.

Basically, I guess we use a lightweight form of slots, but only in kilo-3, based on the exception freeze process, but more informed by the pre agreed project priorities.

We still keep the end of kilo-3 as the string freeze, doc impacting freeze, etc, as normal. By which I mean, the under the radar feature-ish patches can still go in, along side bugs, during kilo-3.

The major reasoning behind this, is to try and get more people to help with the bug backlog and stabilisation process, and give more "space" for high priority things at the end of the release.

Now, leaving this to kilo-3 means we could decide to pull the plan, if things are "going well" during kilo-1 and kilo-2.


One other thing we need to discuss, is moving specs from juno into kilo, but lets cover that later.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-11 19:01:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

we can revisit this at a later date if we choose'}]

commit_message:
Add plan for kilo blueprints: runways

At the nova mid-cycle we agreed that while specs have mode are blueprint
process significantly better, we think the current approach still leaves
much to be desired. This document is the outcome of the discussion at
the mid-cycle on how we want to manage blueprints in Kilo.

This proposal is being placed in devref, as we want to use gerrit's
workflow (two core reviews, inline comments, revisions etc) and this is
a document for developers.

Change-Id: Idcb4549a0c91cbb133f120fba271c26ec635feb7

commit_message:
Fix problem with cloud-init on nova-network

Add datasource modules, which are not included as default
on Ubuntu 14.04.

Change-Id: I645ea17c14960e12bf8649526273e2d7c619c25f
Closes-bug: #1375645

commit_message:
Add more neutron section attrbutes

Added a few more needed neutron attributes.  Currently the nova.conf
does not use new neutron section for these, but will leave that for another bug.

Change-Id: Ia8790c76798595de54642961ada2debdf1dd9350
Closes-Bug: #1378007

commit_message:
Add an extra parameter for test directory in debugger script

The `python-*client`'s usually give back the full package name
i.e. python-keystoneclient, and the script assumes thats where
the tests are, but most clients have their tests under just
*client, or in this case keystoneclient.
Oslo projects have a similar issue.
Change the debug script to accept an optional argument that can
be used to override the guesstimated value.

Change-Id: If0a25ae7ab9f854f87271a377dd228e2ebfb107f

commit_message:
Set install_command in tox to avoid pre-releases

tox (lovingly) uses the --pre option with pip. We don't want that, so
override the install_command with a version that doesn't include it.

Change-Id: I0b8e48488d5c138c0aac85df2336b2340d7c59c4
Closes-Bug: #1379998

The error this resolves is this:
```ruby
        /usr/bin/ruby1.9.1 extconf.rb

        from extconf.rb:5:in `<main>'
```

Change-Id: I3c75e0303ed82ab305f63965ca0c37bdb106ee89

commit_message:
Revert "Ignore sphinx 1.3b1"

This reverts commit 1935f491722999fedd071b0af9d87d85054694ed.

This change was based on an incorrect hypothesis stemming from an
invalid analysis of the problem it was intended to solve. The bug
observed was a misconfiguration in a single project.

Change-Id: I5daa63c664a6e1e05e69886941c700a4d523b59a
Related-Bug: #1379998

commit_message:
Override pip install command under tox

Overriding tox's install_command so it won't default to passing
--pre to pip, and therefore avoid installing prerelease versions of
dependencies.

Change-Id: Ia89d3a16c2bd83f44d6a45c1f4e8e32fd9dfaae6

should recommend the default options.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-11 02:49:18.000000000', 'message': "Don't update a LoadBalancer under autoscaling control

Unfortunately, Autoscaling currently uses the update() method of a
LoadBalancer resource to do updates, with the result that the current
member list gets persisted (good) and used to compare in the event of
future *stack* updates (bad).

With this patch, we assume that LoadBalancers under the control of
Autoscaling will never have a members list property supplied in the
template.  We then ignore any updates to Autoscaling LoadBalancers that
don't actually modify the template.

The test changes revert the changes made in order to be able to merge
d32370233eaf2a5c32888f269bd1dc5e0e787467, before which LoadBalancers were
behaving correctly.

Change-Id: I9c02ab3d3dfbee0a8a90dd0ba345a5acdaf8a610
Closes-Bug: #1379619
(cherry picked from commit 7506d2c22fcd3d6e825ee660a4b20c5947cc7e9a)
"}]
commit_message:
Don't update a LoadBalancer under autoscaling control

Unfortunately, Autoscaling currently uses the update() method of a
LoadBalancer resource to do updates, with the result that the current
member list gets persisted (good) and used to compare in the event of
future *stack* updates (bad).

With this patch, we assume that LoadBalancers under the control of
Autoscaling will never have a members list property supplied in the
template.  We then ignore any updates to Autoscaling LoadBalancers that
don't actually modify the template.

The test changes revert the changes made in order to be able to merge
d32370233eaf2a5c32888f269bd1dc5e0e787467, before which LoadBalancers were
behaving correctly.

Change-Id: I9c02ab3d3dfbee0a8a90dd0ba345a5acdaf8a610
Closes-Bug: #1379619
(cherry picked from commit 7506d2c22fcd3d6e825ee660a4b20c5947cc7e9a)

commit_message:
Make sure that the properties are stored on updates

Previously properties_data was only stored on creation, now
this is getting passed to the update mechanism too.
Later we can look at reworking this into a single mechanism.

Closes-bug: #1377681
Change-Id: If3d476f34b9e61a3c99f63ba33734a875353c8fc
(cherry picked from commit d32370233eaf2a5c32888f269bd1dc5e0e787467)

commit_message:
Fix quota limit range validator

In Quota model limit is defined with Integer type which in case of
MySQL and PostgreSQL is always stored in 4 bytes. At the same time,
the current validator checks that the value does not exceed sys.maxsize
which depends on whether the system is 32-bit or 64-bit based.

In SQLite Integer can be stored in 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, or 8 bytes depending
on the magnitude of the value. Nevertheless, assume that it can not
exceed 4 bytes for consistency.

Limited the upper bound of the validator with 2**31 - 1.

Added a unit test.

Closes-Bug: #1338479
Change-Id: Icefa2fc228e4255a022d586cab4590607953d1ee

commit_message:
coraid: allow setting default repository

Currently, the Coraid driver requires storing Storage Repository
name in volume type key named 'coraid_repository' or different key name
if a value of the 'coraid_repository_key' option changed in the cinder
configuration file.

In case of creating a volume without volume type associated or creating
a volume with volume type that doesn't have an appropriate key with
the repository name, volume creation fails.

That is an inconvenient behaviour, especially in case of using that with
Tempest that creates new volume types but obviously doesn't know
that it should add keys with the repository name.

In order to fix that, introduce a 'coraid_default_repository' config
option that allows to set a default repository to use if one is not
specified in the volume type key.

In case if neither volume type nor config file provide a repository
name, throw CoraidException with description of the problem.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib205553cdee0af0036a774f6926433f4452ec023

commit_message:
gitignore /.*

Ignore all dotfiles in the base dir of the tree except for
.gitignore, .coveragerc, .mailmap, and .testr.conf.

This should solve the "ignore my IDE's files" problem in a
general way.

Change-Id: Ia53fff4b97e4e99b6827030573973377beddb22b

commit_message:
VMware: Bump driver version

Commit 86591a24d48fe19be427b5a8981821fcdb85bb37 added support for
retype API in VMDK driver. This patch updates the driver version
to reflect this.

Change-Id: I8351a40d393d68f5873237fb670a5e0c4a93a863

As part of given BP, community decided to add next Mgmt API.
New mgmt API routes for pollster should be added:

GET {tenant_id}/mgmt/stats/instances

GET {tenant_id}/mgmt/stats/backups

Ceilometer can read and process notifications that were sent at any stage, but there's not way for Ceilometer to get information about all Trove instances/backups. The Only one way to achive this requirement - implement new API that gives an ability to query info about all running instances in real-time (which cannot be accomplished with Ceilometer, because it manipulates only with notifications that were sent long time ago). commit_message:
Add instance/backups stats API

Reasons:
 - for admin users would be very useful to have certain
   set of API calls that'll provide certain stats
   for managed resources for all/or-per tenant(s).

Changes:
 - added new API extension:
   - instance stats for all/per tenant(s);
   - backup stats for all/per tenant(s);

Partially Implements: blueprint ceilometer-integration
DocImpact: 4 new shell commans for instances/backups stats views:
           - <resource>-stat-list;
           - <resource>-stat-show <tenant_id>

Change-Id: I5b5d2893a65d12f4a1c04d098fb6ae39e7c82330

commit_message:
Add mgmt API for datastores

Implemented mgmt API calls for create/update datastores/versions.
To access this API call "admin" role is required.
Removed datastores related commands from trove-manage.
Changed response from datastore-list, now regular user can see only
datastores which has atleast one active version.

Changes:
 - updated the way of datastores are being registered
   while calling ./redstack kick-start <datastore>

Partially implements: blueprint datastores-mgmt-api

Depends-On: I01c0ecc276a73fbbc06ec39bfaa1c66f47fc3a9c Trove
Depends-On: Iee7ed7b141548ef64231acad6319e769d356b97f python-troveclient

Change-Id: I49195c2c8c08fe4673b2dc69d86ea16ee7654431
